column16: Is a born leader. Can play all three forward positions and any role on a hockey club. Possesses a good shot and great defensive instincts.
column17: Has a tendency to run hot and cold in the scoring department, which makes him overrated offensively. Isn't a great passer.
column18: Two-way center and leader, but on the decline
column19: Broken left Index finger, Injured reserve (IR)

column16: Is a fast skater and a responsible performer in the defensive zone. Uses his size effectively, works hard and defends his teammates.
column17: Has a very limited offensive arsenal and lacks hockey sense. His aggressive nature leads to injuries. Lacks game-to-game consistency.

column16: Is a solid enforcer that can also play a regular shift. Skates pretty well for a tough guy. Owns an excellent slap shot.
column17: Needs to polish his defensive work in order to potentially move up to the third line. Misses a lot of scoring opportunities.

column16: Loves to hit people. Plays with tremendous intensity and grit. Is a very popular player in the dressing room. Possesses a great point shot, which produces a good number of goals. Can shut down opposing forwards with aplomb. Is also a good pugilist.
column17: Has difficulty defending some of the quickest forwards in the NHL, since he struggles with quick turns. Is prone to taking the occasional bad penalty. Doesn't have the speed to rush up ice with the puck consistently.

column16: Is very slick and has great vision on the ice. Makes crisp, tape-to-tape passes. Has excellent size for the center position. Can also play wing if the need arose.
column17: Is not a natural goal-scorer, so defenders often look for the pass. Must do more in the postseason. Injuries have dogged him throughout his career.

column16: Handles the puck with panache and can make spectacular saves. Is extremely athletic and a master of the poke-check. Moves well across the crease and has a flair for the dramatic.
column17: When he loses focus, he goes into a bit of tailspin that can last for several games. Can be beaten upstairs because he's undersized. Occasionally lets in a softie.

column16: Is one of hockey's most dedicated players. Loves to battle for loose pucks and crash the net with authority. Has soft hands and is still a tough customer.
column17: Injuries are always a concern with him, especially now that he's over 40. His highly aggressive play is a quality but it does also lead to bad penalties, at times.

column16: Possesses great on-ice vision and creates numerous scoring chances for his linemates. Uses his reach to make things happen. Has terrific size and strength with the puck.
column17: Doesn't score as many goals as his talent suggests, and could stand to shoot the puck more often. Can be thrown off his game in critical spots. Is a bit too passive.

column16: Is a feared and imposing figure along the blue-line. Uses his size to deliver big hits. Excels in the shot-blocking department and possesses a hard shot from the point.
column17: Sometimes, he gets caught out of position in trying to go for the big hit. Is not a polished passer, and doesn't excel when placed on the power play.

column16: Has great size and decent speed for his 6-3 frame. Can play either along the blueline or as an imposing winger.
column17: Needs to fine-tune his overall game. Must gain more experience and improve his hockey sense in order to earn more ice time.

column16: Is an excellent garbage goal-scorer, usually paying a steep physical price in front of the net. Isn't shy about hitting opponents back and works very hard. Can play on either wing.
column17: Is only an average performer in five-on-five situations. Lacks consistency and has a tendency to take bad penalties in the offensive zone.
column18: Complementary winger and front-of-the-net specialist on the power play

column16: Goes full-tilt all the time. Has good speed and tenacity. Plays a solid two-way game and displays plenty of versatility.
column17: Not blessed with great NHL size at 5-10, 180 pounds. Could also use more confidence in the offensive zone.

column16: Is a load to line up against, at 6-4, 218 pounds. Plays solid defense and is also a capable playmaker. Can chip in with timely goals.
column17: Lacks speed. Isn't very aggressive for a player with such an imposing frame. Has not reached his full potential on offense.

column16: Is one of the best pugilists of all time. Has the ability to utilize his tremendous size to play keepaway with the puck and create space for his linemates.
column17: His skating is well below NHL standards. Doesn't always drop the gloves to defend teammates, and is a little reluctant to play the enforcer role.

column16: Plays a smart game from the back end. Rarely makes mistakes and usually takes the safe route out of the defensive zone. Has solid all-around ability.
column17: Doesn't play enough of a physical game, which allows opposing forwards to run free in front of the net. Isn't a huge point producer, either.

column16: Has loads of versatility, as well as a sound work ethic. Is a proven point producer at the AHL level. Will do whatever it takes to remain in the NHL.
column17: Is undersized, which places a limit on his overall level of effectiveness--especially on offense. Has not put up good offensive numbers at the NHL level.

column16: Is a great skater and possesses good size. He's a responsible player with agitating qualities. Will even drop the gloves if his team needs it.
column17: Will never score in abundance at the National Hockey League level, mainly because of a general lack of high-end talent.
column19: Lower body injury, Day to day

column16: Has good instincts and defensive prowess. Is strong on his skates and works hard. Excels in checking opposing top centers and killing penalties. Also adept at winning face-offs.
column17: Doesn't produce a lot of points for the amount of ice time he receives at the NHL level. Lacks the instincts to shoot the puck when in good scoring position.

column16: Has good size, and he uses it effectively in the corners. Constantly plays a physical, in-your-face style. Is a solid leader in the dressing room.
column17: Has never developed the scoring touch of a true power forward. He's been beset with injuries, which has forced him to part-time status.

column16: Has a motor that will never stop working. Doesn't shy away from physical contact, despite his lack of size. Can take opponents off their game. Is solid defensively and can win face-offs.
column17: Is prone to injury, due to his kamikaze style of play, and is also a limited point producer at the NHL level. Takes a few bad penalties from time to time.

column16: Is one of the best open-ice hitters in the game, a gifted penalty-killer and face-off man. Has excellent leadership skills and always has his game-face on.
column17: His kamikaze approach to the game leads to a multitude of injuries. Isn't a natural goal-scorer, and goes through stretches without points.

column16: Owns the size and face-off skills of an effective NHL center. Is sound defensively, kills penalties with aplomb and provides a physical presence.
column17: Has never shown enough scoring ability in the NHL. Is prone to injury, which has curtailed his overall development as a checker.

column16: Is at his best when taking the body consistently and keeping his game simple. Can play on either side of the ice. Has leadership qualities.
column17: Is offensively challenged and a below-average skater. In fact, he will never have enough speed to be effective when pinching in from the point.

column16: Can line up at all three forward positions. Has good offensive instincts and a nice scoring touch, particularly at the minor-pro level.
column17: Must play with more consistency whenever he's given opportunities at the highest level. Could help himself by using his 6-2 frame more often.

column16: Excels when blocking shots and in a penalty-killing role. Plays a strong game from the back end. Isn't shy about dishing out hits. Displays great poise as a stay-at-home defender.
column17: Lacks offensive instincts and  will occasionally have lapses in judgment in the defensive zone. Has become somewhat injury-prone over time.

column16: Exceptional skater from the blueline position. Packed a heavy shot from the point, where he played a big man's game when motivated.
column17: Some observers felt he lacked the drive and determination to be the best he could be. Took bad penalties and occasionally made horrible decisions with the puck.

column16: Can log huge minutes and is very durable for his limited size. Is extremely mobile and can to rush with the puck. Has the ability to quarterback the power play. Shoots the puck with accuracy.
column17: Does have difficulty at times when opposed to big NHL forwards and is not generally regarded as a physical defender by any stretch of the imagination.

column16: Is extremely poised and rarely gets rattled after giving up a bad goal. Has tremendous agility and the cockiness needed to play between the pipes.
column17: Has always needed more meat on his bones. Tends to go into prolonged slumps, which has always hurt his ability to cement a starting gig in the NHL.
column18: Quality backup or average starting goaltender

column16: Has a wealth of experience, which he uses to full advantage. Moves exceptionally well in the crease. Never quits on a play.
column17: Has become increasingly prone to injury over time. Doesn't have anything left to prove, so his motivation is not what it used to be. Is a high-maintenance goaltender nowadays.

column16: Possesses a well-rounded package of top-level skills, specifically an excellent skating stride and booming shot from the point. Is very strong and aggressive along the blueline.
column17: Has a tendency to lose his concentration in the defensive zone and give the puck away at the most inopportune moments. Must learn to better harness his aggressive nature.

column16: Possesses one of the most intimidating packages in the league. Has a decent skating stride. Is still one of the best pugilists in the NHL.
column17: Is a bit too deliberate when handling and passing the puck. Doesn't fight as much as he used to and is slowly breaking down over time.

column16: Has excellent speed and puck-handling skills. Possesses good hockey sense and sees the ice very well. His speed makes him a special-teams weapon. Plays well in all three zones.
column17: Isn't overly big and can get pushed around. Hasn't put up the numbers expected of him in his career. Doesn't show a lot of offensive consistency. Is injury-prone.
column19: Torn ACL and MCL, Injured reserve (IR)

column16: Loves to kill penalties and is very difficult to play against. Reliable face-off man has sound offensive instincts.
column17: Doesn't have top-end skills, which makes him better suited to the bottom six these days. Isn't always as physical as he should be.

column16: Is blessed with superb vision. Can put the biscuit right on the tape and creates a lot of opportunities for his linemates. Also owns tremendous desire and defensive savvy.
column17: Lacks confidence in the offensive zone. Isn't very big or much of a physical presence. May not score enough for the second line.

column16: Moves the puck efficiently. Uses his mobility to make up for mistakes made in the defensive zone, either by himself or his partner. Is conscious of the transition game.
column17: Struggles with big forwards in front of the net. Tends to make the occasional blunder from behind the blue-line. Isn't a physical player.

column16: Is a great playmaker and has slick moves. Makes things happen on the ice and tends to make his teammates better. Never backs down from a challenge, on or off the ice. Has plenty of leadership qualities.
column17: Injuries and illness have wreaked havoc on his NHL career, and slowed down production over time. His fireball style leaves him vulnerable, while his small stature limits his effectiveness against bigger centers.

column16: Has relentless energy on the ice and is one of the most durable forwards in the league. Is smart with the puck and a capable playmaker from the wing.
column17: Age has crept up on him, and his hands have left him. Doesn't appear capable of playing a leading role on offense any longer, which used to be his calling card.

column16: Forechecked well and brought a lunch-pail mentality to the arena. Often provided an energy boost for his team and had a decent set of hands. Was fearless and always willing to pay the price for his team and teammates.
column17: Always endured suspect skating ability, which prevented him from becoming an all-star at the NHL level. His agitating qualities lessened with age, as injuries mounted.

column16: Has uncanny hand/eye coordination. Is still a sound playmaker, decent goal-scorer and premier player when deflecting point shots.
column17: Has had to battle a reputation for soft play his entire career. His intensity isn't always present; neither is his two-way game. Is on the decline.

column16: Has a wealth of pro experience and NHL size for the blue-line. Plays the right side of the ice with efficiency. Is an excellent team player.
column17: Has never been able to hold onto a regular job at the NHL level, mainly because of a lack of consistency. Isn't much of an offensive threat.

column16: Is a true team player, and is only concerned with his club's success. Will drop the gloves. Plays a solid game in his own end, is physical and can even play the point on power plays.
column17: Has occasional brain cramps in the defensive zone. Isn't skilled enough to lead the rush on offense. Struggles when given top-pairing defenseman duties and can be beaten by speedy forwards.

column16: Has excellent shiftiness and puck-handling ability. Plays with a sound work ethic and passion for the game. Is fearless when going to the net.
column17: Isn't big and can be prone to injury, since he likes to play in traffic. Has goal-scoring limitations.

column16: Plays a smart, conservative game and doesn't take unnecessary chances. Has a lot of veteran leadership.
column17: Doesn't play with enough toughness. Provides very little offense and struggles in a more offensive system.

column16: Is extremely agile and moves incredibly well laterally. Has sound positional skills as a butterfly goalie and often displays a flair for the dramatic.
column17: Drops to his knees too early and has become somewhat vulnerable on high shots. Has lost focus and concentration over the years, which has hurt his overall value.

column16: Is extremely shifty and sees the ice well. Possesses tremendous offensive instincts. An excellent playmaker, he finds his teammates with precision. Has improved his play without the puck. Can agitate opponents.
column17: Stands only 5-10 and, although feisty, can get outmuscled for the puck in the corners. Isn't the fastest skater and can get under his coach's skin because of a lack of discipline from time to time.

column16: Is savvy enough to be used in most defensive situations. Does a solid job at killing penalties. Plays with perseverance and determination.
column17: Lacks bulk. Needs to continue to do all of the little things, since he's a very limited producer in the offensive zone.

column16: Has an excellent combination of size and hands. When in the groove, he's an impact scorer. Has both a booming shot and a mean streak.
column17: Has struggled with consistency over the course of his career. Doesn't skate as well as he used to, which can lead to lazy penalties.

column16: Possesses the total physical package. Is a tireless worker and plays a smart positional game. Defense is his strength.
column17: Has more offensive ability than his statistics indicate. Goes long stretches without scoring. Will take bad penalties.

column16: In his prime, he was among the best agitators of all time. Known as a clutch performer, he saves his best work for the postseason.
column17: How much gas is left in the tank? His long layoff from competitive hockey has reduced him to role-player status.

column16: Is an excellent skater and playmaker. Has racked up points at every level. Is an important player on special teams and a decent face-off man.
column17: Usually avoids heavy traffic areas, since he's smallish in stature and not physical. Lacks the offensive consistency to play a first-line role.

column16: Is an extremely efficient penalty-killer. Solid on the forecheck, he has the grit needed to do battle in the corners. Plays an exemplary team game.
column17: Has not shown the same scoring touch in the pros that he displayed at Boston University. Is prone to long scoring droughts.

column16: Plays a sound defensive game. Can fill in at all three forward positions and has ideal size for a checking line player.
column17: Has lost the scoring touch that was once very promising in the junior ranks. Injuries curtailed a once-promising NHL career.

column16: Displays tremendous exuberance on every shift. Can play center or wing. Is a sound defensive forward.
column17: Doesn't own natural offensive skills. Shoulder problems have plagued him throughout his career.

column16: Has impressive wheels, a booming shot he isn't afraid to unleash, great hand/eye coordination and excellent penalty-killing instincts. Can also play the point on the power play and all three forward positions.
column17: Doesn't have natural playmaking skills and isn't a very physical player, despite good size. Is slowing down with time and a little high-maintenance because he doesn't always play well within the system.

column16: Is supremely skilled with the puck, can finish plays and skates extremely well. Has a wealth of determination and perseverance. Leads by example.
column17: At 5-9, 173 pounds, he can be an easy man to knock off the puck. Must make constant adjustments against physical defenders. Injuries have hurt him over time.

column16: A quick release and deceptive shot from anywhere are keys to his game, since he can score goals with aplomb when on his game. Can line up on either wing.
column17: Gets rattled in physical contests. Is not great in his own zone and generally lacks consistency. Can also be prone to injury due to a lack of size and strength.

column16: Skilled and creative, Zelepukin was a strong two-way presence in the NHL, where he enjoyed his best years with the New Jersey Devils. Well-liked by his teammates, he was part of the 1995 Stanley Cup-winning Devils. Surprisingly gritty.
column17: His offense tailed off late in his NHL career, but that was due more to injury (eye) and a change in role than anything else.

column16: Likes to pinch in from the point. Has good NHL size and plays well in transition from the back end when he's on his game.
column17: Must start banging more bodies with his 6-1, 208-pound frame. Needs to show more consistency at the NHL level.

column16: Has good size and physical presence in the defensive zone. Possesses an acurate shot from the point and leadership qualities.
column17: Lacks the consistency needed to play a top-four defenseman role in the NHL. Isn't a major offensive threat. Has slowed down over time.

column16: Plays with both poise and passion between the pipes. Can make a spectacular save look routine. Can fill in as a starting goalie in a pinch.
column17: Has problems with long shots on occasion. Isn't durable enough to play 60-plus games in the National Hockey League.

column16: Possessed a terrific combination of vision and leadership. Was one of the best skating defensemen in NHL history. Had awesome recuperative ability. Thrived with loads of ice time.
column17: Since he saw so much ice time, there were times when he wasn't as physical as he should have been. Age also curtailed his all-around game a little in the end, though he was still elite throughout.

column16: Has great size and loves to use it. Is an excellent leader by example and usually plays through pain. Knows how to block shots.
column17: Like many big-hitting defensemen, he needs to learn to pick his spots better and not leave himself out of position.

column16: Packs a big shot from the point--one of the best in the game. Has natural leadership qualities and takes on all comers to protect his teammates. Is adept at clearing the front of the net.
column17: Can get beat one on one, due to questionable lateral skating and mobility. Can at times cough up the puck when rushing up ice. Is somewhat injury-prone and can also take bad penalties.
column18: Big-shooting defenseman with a mean streak

column16: Is difficult to play against because he's shifty and unpredictable. Has terrific moves and a scoring touch. Puts up huge numbers in Europe.
column17: Needs to get stronger, both physically and mentally, in order to be as successful in North America as he is in Europe. Is considered soft in the NHL.

column16: Is simply one of the best puck-handling goaltenders of all time. Has the ability to dominate a contest. Excels in games with low shot totals, due to superior concentration.
column17: Plays too much during the regular season and can wear down by the time the playoffs roll around. Can struggle when the system breaks down in front of him.

column16: Uses his big frame to his advantage. Stands up to shooters and cuts down angles with confidence. Handles the puck well with his stick.
column17: Is not as effective when he flops down to his knees. Needs to show more durability and overcome persistent groin problems.

column16: Is sound defensively and loves to throw his weight around. Works very hard and is a strong forechecker. Will do whatever it takes for his team.
column17: Does not score enough at the NHL level to see regular playing time. Has lost a little skating speed since a serious knee injury in 2000-01.

column16: Plays a strong, two-way game. Always leads by example. Excels in penalty-killing situations and on face-offs. A true warrior, he plays through pain.
column17: Has occasional scoring droughts, especially in terms of goals. Isn't as prolific as he used to be, as father time has caught up to him.

column16: Possesses good skills and excellent hockey sense. Can line up on either side of center and owns untapped scoring potential.
column17: Has fought inconsistency throughout his career. Contract squabbles have ruined what was a promising NHL career.

column16: Is very effective in a defensive role and when killing penalties. Will not back down from anyone. Can be agitating to play against. Leads by example.
column17: Lacks size, especially for someone who doesn't mind dropping the gloves on occasion. Will never be confused with a natural goal-scorer.

column16: Owns a wealth of International and minor-pro experience. Is capable of playing a spectacular brand of hockey, in spurts, between the pipes in the NHL.
column17: Needs to show more consistency from game to game. Isn't big, so he doesn't always cover enough of the net on a regular basis. Injuries are a concern.

column16: Is an immovable object in front of the net and the slot area. Possesses one of the hardest shots in the league. Has terrific presence along the boards and excellent hand/eye coordination.
column17: His wonky back is a major question mark at this stage of his career. Has lost a step and isn't as sound defensively as in years past.

column16: Sees the ice well and gets the puck to an open man effectively. Usually plays with intensity and doesn't back down from challenges. Can play both wing and center.
column17: Lacks consistency in all facets of the game. At times, his instigating qualities can be detrimental to his team. He's also a below-average skater.

column16: Is never out of a play, and is one of the most competitive 'keepers in the league. Isn't easily rattled and is able to bounce back from a bad goal. Owns ice water for veins.
column17: While he has proven capable of handling heavy workloads, he isn't as consistent when not given enough rest during the regular season.

column16: Is extremely tough to get a read on from a shooter's perspective because he's unpredictable. Can get red-hot for long stretches and has superb agility.
column17: When he's cold, he tends to lose his focus. Doesn't show enough consistency to be considered an elite-level netminder at the NHL level.

column16: Has a pure goal-scorer's mentality. Possesses an accurate wrist shot and sound offensive instints.
column17: Has yet to prove he can be a consistent scorer in the NHL. Could use more upper-body strength.

column16: Possesses good speed, which he uses efficiently in all three zones. Is an excellent penalty-killer and can play effectively on either side of center.
column17: Lacks the size needed to constantly win battles along the boards. Hasn't produced a lot of points at the NHL level.

column16: Moves the puck efficiently up the ice. Has enough hockey sense to play sound defense when he keeps his game simple. Blocks shots with aplomb and can log big minutes.
column17: Doesn't make good enough use of his big frame from a physicality standpoint, so forwards can get an edge on him. Is somewhat injury-prone.

column16: Is a quick skater and he sees the ice well. Unleashes a hard, accurate shot from the point. Has ideal size for an NHL defenseman.
column17: Is guilty of defensive brain cramps in his own zone. Has never put up numbers to match his potential. He's a player in sharp decline in all aspects of the game.

column16: Possesses a tremendous physical package and plenty of pro experience. Is effective in the corners and can play either wing position if need be.
column17: Has not been able to shake the tag of chronic underachiever. Doesn't use his size nearly enough to maximize his offensive game. Misses too many chances.

column16: Has the ability to recover and never quits on a play, regardless of how awkward he looks. Owns the ability to steal victories from time to time.
column17: His confidence is at times fragile, which leads to bouts of inconsistency. He'll also let in the occasional brain-cramp goal that leave coaches perplexed.

column16: Possesses two of the strongest legs ever seen on a hockey player. Has incredible instincts. Is equally strong setting up linemates or finishing.
column17: Can at times be a moody teammate, or struggle within the confines of a defensive system. Is not a great defender and not always a team player.

column16: Owns the soft hands of a natural goal-scorer. His wrist shot is a bullet and he uses it often to bury his chances. Skates very well for a 6-3, 225-pound winger.
column17: Could use his size more effectively in the offensive zone. Is only an average defensive forward. Has been more prone to injury later in his career.

column16: Has a great shot and excellent hockey sense. Vaulted into stardom once he became a grittier performer. Is a quiet leader and quality teammate.
column17: Is starting to show signs of aging. Needs a quality setup man to play with in order to put up numbers expected of him. Has struggled during the postseason.

column16: Is versatile enough to play all three forward positions. Owns a defensive conscience, some offensive skills and excellent quickness. Has produced at lower levels.
column17: Is small in stature and a non-factor in terms of providing physical toughness. Lacks consistency in the point-production department.

column16: Is a nifty playmaker. Has excellent two-way ability and face-off skills. Knows where to be at all times. Adds versatility to any lineup.
column17: Can go long stretches without scoring a goal. Doesn't use his body to win battles enough. Is declining in terms of production.

column16: Is versatile enough to play both defense and forward. Moves the puck well from the back end and adds leadership skills.
column17: Has not shown the same offensive instincts he had as a college point man. Is too fragile to play a major role along the blueline.

column16: Brings a lot of physical presence to the lineup. Hits early and often. Will not back down from anyone. Can line up both on defense and at left wing.
column17: Lacks skating speed and quickness. May not be able to handle the NHL's best finesse forwards, especially to the outside.

column16: Has great size and very strong defensive instincts. Is hard to line up against and can play both center and wing.
column17: Will occasionally take bad penalties. Isn't a natural when passing the puck, which limits his effectiveness in the offensive zone.

column16: Has an unmatched set of offensive skills with the puck. Is perhaps the premier stickhandler in the game. Displays mesmerizing moves and a deceptive shot. Saves his best for clutch situations.
column17: Will occasionally suffer brain cramps on the ice, resulting in careless turnovers. Tends to lose focus, which can last several games. Lacks defensive polish.

column16: Has solid goal-scoring ability from the back end, mainly due to an explosive point shot. Is an excellent power-play contributor overall.
column17: Has to tighten up defensively. Needs to make better use of his 6-2, 200-pound frame. Must also to a better job of avoiding the injury bug.

column16: Loves to use his breakaway speed, especially on the outside. Can play all three forward positions but is especially useful in the face-off zone.
column17: Needs to pay more attention to detail, since he doesn't possess enough of an offensive game to be a top six forward at the NHL level.

column16: Has boundless offensive talent. Possesses one of the best wrist shots in the game and is a fine playmaker.
column17: Must show more consistency on a year-to-year basis. Doesn't use his 6-3 frame to full advantage.

column16: Has great size at 6-4, 235 pounds. Is a good team player. Can play defense, his original position, if necessary.
column17: Has little to offer in the offensive department. Needs help with his lateral mobility. Doesn't have enough talent to play regularly at any position.

column16: Is a very hard hitter and solid team player. Plays effectively when he stays within his limitations. Is an above-average fighter.
column17: Has major skating deficiencies. Is vulnerable against speedy wingers. Can hurt his team with bad penalties. Isn't talented enough to log regular minutes.

column16: Has extraordinary vision from the back end, makes perfect passes out of his zone and can still act as a fourth forward on the attack.
column17: Has been prone to mental mistakes over the years, due to fatigue from logging too much ice time. Gets caught out of position frequently.

column16: Is a very creative player that is usually aware of his surroundings. Makes smart decisions with the puck. Skates very well. Can play the point on power plays.
column17: Lacks consistency on offense, especially in the goal-scoring department. Isn't strong enough to handle bigger, more dominant centers. Injuries are always a concern.

column16: Knows his role as a stay-at-home defender and takes care of business in his own end first and foremost. Loves a rough-and-tumble game. Is a fabulous hitter and solid leader.
column17: Is not offensively skilled at all. Has virtually no point shot to speak of. May struggle at times against the speedier forwards in the league.

column16: Outstanding passing skills and extremely agile. Ultra smooth, he racked up the assists totals. Great hockey sense, made the right play at the right time.
column17: Not physical, he was overmatched at times when opposed to big forwards in front of the net. Injuries became a concern late in his NHL stint.

column16: Always displays solid leadership qualities. Uses speed, grit and tenacity to play a sound checking game. Is also versatile enough to occasionally play on a scoring line.
column17: Is somewhat limited in the creativity department, and is miscast when used on a scoring line for long stretches. Has become more injury-prone over time.
column18: Veteran checking winger with leadership qualities

column16: Is extremely competitive, which usually rubs off on his teammates in a positive way. Has good size and experience as a starting goalkeeper.
column17: Loses concentration and focus, especially when there's an abundance of traffic in front of his crease. Injuries have curtailed his potential.

column16: Has an impeccable work ethic and never takes a shift off. Is smooth and polished in all aspects of the game. Possesses oodles of creativity. Kills penalties well and can play the point on power plays.
column17: Is often misunderstood in the leadership department because he's not a rah-rah type. His hard-working style of play can lead him to wear down over the course of the season.

column16: Is fearless and can get under an opponent's skin. Possesses open-ice hitting ability and defensive prowess. Is much stronger than his size suggests. Can play both center and wing.
column17: Has limited scoring ability. Tends to take bad penalties. Is breaking down physically because of his rambunctious style of play.

column16: Looks after his own zone first and foremost, but also possesses some puck-moving ability. Rarely gets caught out of position and is an outstanding skater.
column17: Doesn't produce enough points for his skill level and, at this point in his career, probably never will. He's also not as physical as he could be.

column16: Has terrific quickness, excellent finishing qualities and the ability to set up teammates. Can play any forward position and is very sportsmanlike.
column17: Can be thrown off his game with physical play. Has had a history of getting hurt, which have somewhat limited his strong level of play.

column16: Has produced points at every level below the NHL. Is a sound two-way performer and an agitating forward to play against. Can play all three forward positions.
column17: Is paper thin and not physically capable of handling the NHL's biggest and roughest customers in the corners. Lacks consistent production.

column16: Thinks like a goal-scorer and is willing to pay the price in front of the net to score goals. Can play a feisty game. Is capable of lining up on either side of center.
column17: Is only average in the defensive zone. Still drifts too much and needs to focus more on playing 60 minutes every night. Is inconsistent in the hitting department.

column16: Plays an up-and-down game, is strong along the wall and is willing to play a physical brand of hockey. Can score at lower levels.
column17: Is a limited skater and finisher in the NHL. Seems to lack consistency in terms of doing the little things needed to stay in the big league.

column16: Loves to stir up the opposition, and is an asset in front of the net. Is a solid skater who likes to dish out hits when the opportunity knocks. Works well along the boards and can line up on either side of center.
column17: Is a little smallish in stature, which works against him when trying to play a big man's game. Has lacked consistency in the NHL, especially in terms of his offensive production.

column16: Has tremendous quickness and elusiveness. Is a sound defensive player and spark plug on offense. Owns a motor that never quits.
column17: Tends to get battered around because of his style of play and lack of size. Has had a brutal run with hard-luck injuries.

column16: Has lightning-quick reflexes and the ability to snatch a sure goal away from opponents with his great glove hand. Challenges shooters well and is confident.
column17: His circus-save approach leads to occasional overreactions to certain shots. Can at times give up weak goals. Must step up in big-game situations.

column16: Is very strong and difficult to knock off the puck. Has a knock for getting into ideal scoring position. Can unleash a wicked shot from the slot area.
column17: His attitude and demeanor have constantly come into question throughout his career. Must start showing more production during postseason play. Is a high-maintenance superstar with below-average defensive ability.

column16: Has good size and is very strong. Possesses a terrific shot from the point and can be a solid point producer. Can also log plenty of minutes.
column17: Tends to struggle against speedy wingers and occasionally makes critical mistakes in the defensive zone. Lacks consistency in the physicality department.

column16: Has great size and mobility. Can log a ton of ice time and also play a shutdown role, if required. Is a power-play asset due to a heavy shot from the point.
column17: Should use his size more to keep forwards honest but is not physical enough for a 6-3 defenseman. Is guilty of occasional brain cramps and can be a little injury-prone.
column19: Lower body injury, Day to day

column16: Possesses a huge frame and good speed for such a big man. Has excellent puck-handling skills and untapped scoring potential.
column17: Lacks the desire and drive needed to become a quality NHLer. Has always displayed questionable work ethic. Disappears for lengthy stretches.

column16: Has an excellent shot and the poise needed to play a role on the power play. When he keeps the game simple, he's very effective and logs a ton of ice time.
column17: Is prone to the occasional mental blunder. Will put himself out of position in search of the big open-ice hit.

column16: Has terrific size and mobility from the back end. Displays both decent offensive instincts and a sound defensive approach. Is also a low-maintenance defender.
column17: At 6-4, 226 pounds, he doesn't make good use of his imposing frame. Is still lacking in consistency and rarely raises his game to another level.

column16: Is a quietly effective player in the offensive zone. Knows when to join the attack and displays excellent instincts. Is also a steady defender.
column17: Doesn't use his size enough and has trouble keeping big forwards in check. Lacks shutdown ability. Is in serious decline offensively.

column16: Moves the puck quickly and effectively out of the defensive zone. Is a very heady player with solid all-around ability. Steps up in big spots. Is always willing to take a hit to make a play.
column17: Should produce more points with his skill set, but has trouble providing consistent offense. Can struggle against big forwards and is prone to bone-jarring hits in the defensive zone.

column16: Uses his long reach effectively to fend off on-rushing forwards. Is smart at pinching in from the point. Usually plays within his limitations.
column17: Could use some more meat on his bones. Lacks offensive flair. Doesn't have a nasty streak in him and is somewhat uncoordinated.

column16: Has a good-sized frame and some NHL experience. When he's on his game, he's keeping things clean and tidy in the defensive zone.
column17: Has too many limitations to be taken seriously at the NHL level. Doesn't have a lot of offensive upside.

column16: Is a great shot-blocker. Has tremendous size and reach. Excels on the penalty kill and in shutdown roles. Can log a lot of minutes and has pretty good hockey sense. Can also be a leader.
column17: Has skating deficiencies that hurt his overall effectiveness, since he can get beat to the outside. Isn't much of an offensive threat.

column16: Has an above-average array of offensive skills at lower levels. Owns one of the hardest shots in pro hockey. Is capable of running a power play.
column17: His defensive game has always held him back, as it's well below-average by NHL standards. Cannot be trusted with big minutes at the highest level.

column16: Packs a mean punch and is always ready and willing to fight anyone at any time. Never complains about ice time.
column17: Lacks the requisite skills to play regularly in the NHL. Is a defensive liability. Can at times get carried away on the ice.

column16: Has great hands and a lethal shot. Hits everything in sight. Excels at taking face-offs. Knows where to be to score goals.
column17: Could still improve his defensive game. Must show more discipline on and off the ice. Takes too many nights off.

column16: Possesses work ethic that is second to none. Has sound two-way and penalty-killing ability. Can play in any situation.
column17: Will never contend for any scoring records. Is a dedicated checker, but his lack of bulk can be a disadvantage when shutting down big power forwards.

column16: Has intimidating speed, especially when he takes it to the outside, and a great slap shot. Plays with veteran savvy and a defensive conscience.
column17: Has difficulty fighting through the neutral-zone trap. Still plays a passive game and needs a quality setup man in order to put up good numbers.

column16: Lethal scorer from the slot area. Loves to instigate trouble for the opposition. Plays a sound two-way game and is very durable.
column17: Is not as intimidating as he was in the early 90's, at least in terms of his physical presence. Has become a streaky scorer over time.

column16: Is a tenacious forechecker and solid penalty-killer. Plays with an abundance of energy. Shows excellent team play and work ethic. Is defensively sound and a good face-off man.
column17: Lacks the hands of a goal-scorer. Tends to wear down physically the more he's used. Is a limited talent in all facets of the game.

column16: Has terrific hockey sense and on-ice awareness. Is defensively responsible and an excellent face-off man.
column17: Is undersized and a bit fragile. Hasn't produced numbers in the NHL that match his talent level.

column16: Is an above-average skater from the back end. Works hard and loves to dish out punishment. Has the ability to play on the power play.
column17: Gets into trouble whenever he goes out of his way to land a big hit. Injuries are always a concern due to the hard-nosed style of game he plays.

column16: Is extremely reliable in the defensive zone. Shows great leadership among his fellow rearguards. Plays against top talent and usually holds his own.
column17: Should play a more physical game but doesn't. Hasn't put up big offensive numbers since his days with the Boston Bruins.

column16: Possesses sound work ethic and leadership qualities. Is a renowned AHL performer with the ability to step into an NHL lineup in a pinch.
column17: Is already too old to be considered a prospect and not talented enough to play a regular shift at the NHL level. Doesn't capitalize enough on his chances.

column16: Is an outstanding penalty-killer and shutdown pivot. His versatility enables him to play any role on a hockey club. Has great speed, sound fundamentals and an excellent work ethic.
column17: Doesn't put up huge numbers in the NHL, which makes him a less-than-ideal top six pivot. Can go long stretches without a point.

column16: Is extremely poised and has the ideal demeanor for a goaltender. Plays a textbook butterfly style. Covers most of the net with his large frame.
column17: Tends to be vulnerable whenever his positioning leaves him. Doesn't handle the puck well and doesn't improvise either.

column16: Has incredible reflexes and excellent lateral movement. Will never quit on a play. Can steal a victory from time to time.
column17: Isn't as effective when given 60-65 starts, since he lacks durability. His lack of size can be exploited by NHL snipers.

column16: Was one of the most durable NHLers of his time. Good speed and a hard shot. With a nose for the net, he was a very flashy player when hot.
column17: Mainly an offensive player, he could struggle defensively when his game was out of sync. Not much of a physical player, he was paid to score goals.

column16: Has excellent size for a goaltender and covers a lot of the net physically. Is experienced in the minor-pro game and shows an exemplary attitude.
column17: Needs to work on lateral mobility in order to take the next step in his development. Has yet to make the most of his NHL opportunities.

column16: Owns a solid work ethic and is strong along the boards. Is also willing to crash the net to create scoring chances or even drop the gloves.
column17: Lacks polish in his overall offensive game. Will never light up the score sheet at the National Hockey League level.

column16: Has good speed, skill and versatility. Can score in streaks and is a solid player in the defensive zone. Kills penalties with aplomb.
column17: Plays a soft game along the boards and lacks muscle. Has a limited offensive arsenal. Needs to show more consistency in his overall game.

column16: Has natural leadership skills. Boasts good size and loads of checking acumen. Works extremely hard night in, night out. Is effective on the penalty kill.
column17: Injuries have played a major part in his career and curtailed offensive expectations. Hasn't been able to show the anticipation or timing needed to score goals consistently.

column16: Is still capable of scoring big goals. Keeps things light in the dressing room. Has become more versatile over time.
column17: Has had knee problems that have hindered his production over the years. Is an emotional athlete that can be thrown off his game.

column16: Sound in his own end and often responsible for shutting down the opposition's best players. Durability and size to play a physical defensive game. Leads by example.
column17: Like most stay-at-home defensemen, lacks the offensive prowess that garners media and fan attention.

column16: Was one of the toughest defensemen to beat one-on-one throughout his career. Always played a smart game in the defensive zone and was terrific in transition. Was also a nasty individual to line up against.
column17: No longer supplied his club with quality offensive production or huge amounts of ice time in the second half of his extremely lengthy career.
column18: One of the all-time greatest defensemen

column16: Is as mobile as they come from the back end. Runs a power play smoothly and with creativity. Puts up impressive point totals and is solid in the defensive zone. Can act as a fourth forward when on the ice.
column17: Is not big or strong, so he struggles to handle NHL power forwards in front of the net. Tries to do too much with the puck from time to time.

column16: Has terrific hand/eye coordination. Displays excellent instincts at both ends of the ice. Can line up at all three forward positions. Is good on face-offs and when killing penalties.
column17: Doesn't display enough offensive consistency. Is somewhat fragile and slender, so he could use more bulk to help with the rigors of the National Hockey League schedule.

column16: Is a hard-working energy forward that earns a lot of respect in standing up for his teammates. Has strong forechecking and penalty-killing skills. Tends to rattle his opponents with hits and an in-your-face attitude. Can play any forward position. Is great at blocking shots.
column17: Gets hurt a lot because he's always putting his body on the line. Will never lead his NHL team in scoring and is somewhat limited in terms of natural ability. Some of his on-ice antics that rile up the opposition are questionable.
column18: Energy forward, warrior and leader with defensive ability

column16: Is big, strong, tough and determined. He's a far better skater than the average banger. Can win face-offs, play all three forward positions and kill penalties.
column17: Doesn't have much of an offensive arsenal. Will take a few bad penalties on occasion. Plays out of control at times.

column16: Is a hard-hitting winger and willing pugilist. Can be effective in a crash-and-bang setting as a role player.
column17: Lacks the required skills to be anything more than a role player at the NHL level. Is not often on the winning side of fights.

column16: Has great speed and shiftiness. Is extremely durable and versatile. Likes to create plays from the wing position.  Is a dangerous penalty-killer and possesses the heart of a lion.
column17: Doesn't score as much as he sets linemates up, so he could stand to be more selfish.

column16: Plays within his limitations and is always open to instruction. Moves the puck quickly out of the defensive zone. Likes to initiate contact.
column17: Lacks bulk and offensive flair. Tends to take bad penalties in the defensive zone. Owns limited overall ability.

column16: Is an awesome one-on-one defender, has a great reach and can dish out punishing body checks. He's also an excellent power-play point man, due to a big shot. Was born to lead.
column17: Has a tendency to take bad penalties and make questionable hits. Isn't a natural when rushing up the ice with the puck.

column16: Is a quick-skating defenseman. Has the ability to quarterback the power play. Can fill in at a forward position in a pinch.
column17: Doesn't handle traffic in front of the net well. Hasn't put up enough points in the NHL to receive regular playing time. Is a major underachiever.

column16: Loves to play a banging style from behind the blueline. Is an excellent leader. Owns plenty of versatility and is capable of putting up decent totals.
column17: Isn't accurate enough with his shots from the point. Can take bad penalties from time to time, which places his team behind the eight ball.

column16: Has a motor that refuses to quit. Loves to play in the trenches. Has leadership ability and sound defensive skills. Can line up anywhere up front.
column17: Has an extremely limited offensive arsenal. Lacks ideal size for an abrasive forward. Doesn't handle the speed of the NHL well.

column16: Has excellent size, which he uses effectively to shut down scoring forwards. Owns a hard shot from the point. Moves relatively well for a huge man.
column17: Is somewhat injury-prone. Still struggles at times with his lateral mobility. Lacks consistency in the defensive zone.

column16: Was one of the most electrifying goal-scorers in NHL history. Had great hands and skating ability, a flair for the dramatic and offensive instincts.
column17: Was never considered a great defensive player, and often spent too much time outside of the defensive zone. Knee injuries cut his great career short.

column16: Skates well and is difficult to knock off the puck. Can score goals in streaks. Is a good penalty-killer and forechecker. Goes all out every night.
column17: Can go ridiculous stretches without scoring a point. Will never reach his full potential.

column16: An outstanding leader, he commands respect throughout the league and in the room. Is a very responsible two-way forward, and still a factor in big games.
column17: Has not been a major offensive contributor since the 1995-96 campaign. Is clearly on the decline, and can no longer log huge minutes for his team.

column16: Still owns a deadly combination of speed and shooting ability. Has dazzling moves coming down his off-wing (right). Instills fear into opposing defenders with his skill level.
column17: Is no longer as big an offensive weapon as in years past. When he isn't scoring goals, he is a very replaceable part.

column16: Possesses excellent skating speed. Has sound offensive credentials and always gives maximum effort. Can play either center or wing.
column17: Lacks size and strength. Tends to struggle when the checking gets tighter. Is somewhat prone to scoring slumps.

column16: Skates well and plays a solid two-way game up front. Has the versatility to be used on defense if the need arises. Is an excellent teammate.
column17: Could use a finishing touch, and doesn't create a lot of offense as a forward. Goes into prolonged scoring slumps and is inconsistent overall.

column16: Has good NHL size for the wing position and is an excellent bodychecker. Displays two-way potential.
column17: A lack of game-to-game consistency has held him back at the NHL level. Won't score goals at the same pace as he did in lower leagues.

column16: Has a howitzer of a slap shot, handles the puck well and has improved his play in the defensive zone over time. Possesses sound leadership qualities.
column17: Lacks top-level skating ability. Could stand to play with more aggression, especially in the defensive zone. Doesn't shoot enough anymore.

column16: Possesses blinding speed, shiftiness and an ability to make opposing defenders miss. Loves to score goals off the rush.
column17: Still plays out of control at times, and needs to better harness his tremendous speed. Misses a lot of scoring chances.

column16: Has excellent skating ability for a 6-5 defenseman. Physically, he has everything you look for in a rearguard. Is savvy.
column17: Doesn't use his size enough and plays a fairly passive game. Always leaves you wanting more, due to his incredible physical package.

column16: Has blinding speed and incredible recuperative ability on defense. Is excellent in transition, underrated defensively and a leader.
column17: Isn't great on the power play, since he usually plays it safe on offense. Doesn't use his size enough. Injuries are always a concern.

column16: Has size, skating ability, a blast from the blueline and intelligence. Is capable of shutting down the very best forwards in the NHL. Also provides leadership and is a great open-ice hitter.
column17: Is an inconsistent offensive performer. Rarely plays at 100 per-cent health, due to his warrior mentality, which can at times hinder his performance.

column16: Has tremendous heart and leadership qualities. Is an excellent teammate. Can score, work the corners and even fight if the need arises.
column17: Not overly big, he tends to wear down during the course of the 82-game schedule. His lack of size has also caused a slow down in production.

column16: Is well rounded, versatile and a smart forward. Does the little things needed to win hockey games.
column17: Lacks offensive flair. Needs to bulk up more. Is limited to role-player status at the NHL level.

column16: Is a tough customer who's always willing to stick up for his teammates. Can be a very effective enforcer if used sparingly.
column17: Is often caught out of position, mainly because he's still a work-in-progress at the forward position. Needs to avoid taking bad penalties.

column16: Is a tough hombre and likes to work the corners. Possesses tremendous lower-body strength and isn't afraid to drop the gloves.
column17: Lacks the skating polish needed to carve out a regular spot in the lineup at the highest level. Is somewhat offensively challenged.

column16: Owns tremendous offensive instincts. Is at his best when setting up his wingers. Has good face-off skills and plays with an abundance of patience.
column17: Below-average skater. Could stand to shoot more and play a little more selfishly.

column16: Provides his team with energy virtually every game. Can play effectively in a support role on scoring lines or on a shutdown line.
column17: Doesn't have enough bulk to thrive playing an in-your-face style at the NHL level. Has been on a steady decline, production-wise.

column16: Had a deceptively hard wrist shot and liked to use it from anywhere. Was very strong on both special teams and had excellent skating speed in his prime.
column17: Didn't get a lot of assists because he shot the puck so often. Wasn't a physical player but took a few too many penalties.

column16: Has great offensive instincts. Can set up plays and finish them off with equal zest. Is very creative with the puck and positionally sound. Does great work around the opponents' crease.
column17: Is a below-average skater, which prevents him from elevating his play to a top-tier level. Does not initiate a lot of contact, despite having the size to do so.

column16: Used his speed, shiftiness and shot to score a lot of goals in the NHL. Sticked his nose in the corners and used his strong lower body to win many battles. Electrifying, flamboyant player when on a hot streak.
column17: Not a good passer and could always use more work in the defensive zone. Encountered his share of prolonged scoring slumps.

column16: Has good physical tools. Possesses a booming shot and can effectively produce offense at lower levels.
column17: Struggles with defensive-zone coverage. Is mistake-prone. Doesn't use his size nearly enough.

column16: Few can run a power play better than him. Has size, hockey sense and a wicked shot from the point. Makes crisp passes to get out of the defensive zone. Is a constant menace on offense.
column17: Doesn't use the body nearly enough, and can be guilty of lazy play on occasion. Because he sees so much ice time, and is getting on in years, he has become more of an injury risk with time.

column16: Loves to use the body. Plays within his limitations. Is versatile, an excellent presence in the dressing room and the consummate team player.
column17: Lacks skating speed and has a tendency to get injured with relative frequency. Is not suited to the stylings of the \new\" NHL."

column16: Is a strong defender while his team is short-handed and an excellent team leader. Will make his presence felt on every shift. Loves to take the body and isn't afraid of dropping the gloves.
column17: Lacks mobility, and it's not getting better with age. Tends to stray out of position in order to line up his opponent for the big hit. Shows little in the way of offense. Takes too many penalties.

column16: Has tremendous vision and playmaking ability. Is incredibly shifty and often makes opponents miss with their bodychecks. Possesses plenty of scoring prowess.
column17: Doesn't always keep his intensity level on high. Could still use more bulk on his 6-1 frame. Should take more shots so as to keep defenders honest, but doesn't.

column16: Has great size and skating ability from the back end. Excels when given plenty of ice time in a shutdown role against top scorers.
column17: Lacks consistency in the offensive zone. Has stepped up his physical play, but there's still some work to do in that department.

column16: Shows an excellent glove hand and a lot of persistence in the crease area. Is a hard worker and displays the ability to bounce back from adversity.
column17: Doesn't handle the pressure of playing major minutes well and generally lacks consistency.

column16: Can score goals in bunches, and is usually good for one big streak per year. Skates well and has an accurate shot. Knows where to go in order to score.
column17: Should be more of a physical presence on the ice, but he isn't. Needs to become more of a take-charge guy. Has trouble creating his own scoring chances.

column16: Possesses an excellent combination of skill and physical play. Is an outstanding playmaker due to great vision. Is also stellar in his own end.
column17: His penchant for physical play has him often battling serious injuries. Needs to play with less reckless abandon in order to prolong his career.

column16: Is capable of both leading his team in scoring and the dressing room. Has good size and an excellent shot. Also chips in defensively. Can play either wing.
column17: Is inconsistent on offense. Can be brittle because of age and his rugged approach to the game. Can lose his cool on the ice from time to time.

column16: Is a premier face-off man, very responsible in the defensive zone and one of the best back-checking forwards in the NHL. Elevates his play in crucial games.
column17: As the fourth overall pick in 1990, his offensive game has never lived up expectations. Isn't very fast and takes bad penalties.

column16: His speed often has defenders scrambling and he's a very capable one-on-one winger. Has solid defensive instincts and is a threat while short-handed.
column17: Is occasionally prone to defensive lapses and at times can appear disinterested on the ice. Needs to play a lot to be effective. Doesn't use his size enough.

column16: Owns one of the league's best wrist shots. Has smooth skating ability and crafty playmaking skills. Sees the ice well and is rarely out of position.
column17: Throughout his career, he has always overcome his lack of size but it gets more difficult over time. Needs a little more rest than earlier in his career.

column16: Can intimidate any opposing player with his combination of scoring and fighting ability. Has a deadly wrist shot and quick release.
column17: Lacks polish in the defensive zone. Is often guilty of taking bad penalties. Has a history of injury problems.

column16: A good athlete with nice size, he has the classic physical package for an NHL power forward. He has a decent touch around the net and is solid defensively.
column17: Doesn't get the most out of his physical gifts. Doesn't shoot the puck enough for a sniper and isn't a bruiser. Is an underachiever.

column16: Is a good skater and gutsy shot-blocker. Has excellent anticipation when killing penalties or opposing quality centers. Provides leadership and face-off skills.
column17: Has an extremely limited scoring touch. Plays injured a lot, which limits his overall effectiveness. Is starting to wear down physically with time.

column16: Has excellent size and strength. Likes to play a crash-and-bang style in the corners. Displays decent instincts at both ends of the ice.
column17: Lacks top-end skills, so he needs to do the little things better in order to remain in the NHL. Is a below-average skater at the highest level.

column16: Has impressive size and a great attitude. Keeps his game simple and can be counted on to stick up for his mates. Can play either defense or right wing.
column17: Lacks mobility, which prevents him from remaining in the lineup on a regular basis at any position. Doesn't have an offensive game to speak of.

column16: Plays an outstanding defensive game and is very consistent. Is excellent in the dressing room and always leads by example. Often sets the physical tone.
column17: His gung-ho style leads to long-term injuries. Isn't a great puck-handler. Will no longer factor into the power-play mix.

column16: Is an extremely dedicated hockey player. Packs his lunch pail and does whatever is needed to help his team win. Can be solid in a pinch.
column17: Is a limited offensive player. Struggles when given too much of a workload and isn't suited to playing a starring role along the blueline.

column16: Is an extremely industrious forward with plenty of grit and toughness. Is at his best when banging bodies. Will drop the gloves against anyone.
column17: Doesn't have a lot of natural offensive ability, so goals are hard to come by. His skill level for the NHL isn't good enough to log regular ice time.

column16: Plays a steady game behind the blueline and owns great size and mobility. Doesn't do anything flashy but is very reliable without the puck.
column17: Has very little offensive potential. Needs to better utilize his 6-2, 221-pound frame and prove his shoulder can hold up to the rigors of the NHL.

column16: Is big, strong and capable of effectively clearing the front of his own end. Avoids making big mistakes in the defensive zone and constantly displays the attitude of a winner.
column17: Isn't the fleetest skater and needs to be picture perfect in his positional play to avoid getting beat one-on-one. He won't ever provide much offense.

column16: Is technically sound and strong between the ears. Has excellent team qualities and is willing to accept a lesser role to benefit others.
column17: Has yet to prove he can raise his game to the next level. Needs to avoid prolonged slumps that have curbed a once-promising career.

column16: Has tremendous character and is well liked in the dressing room. Usually makes the first save and can be spectacular at times.
column17: Doesn't stand tall in the crease, which hurts his ability to cover the entire net. Also has trouble with forwards that crash the front of the net.

column16: Shows excellent puck patience and is not afraid to mix it up. Goes to the net well and plays a solid two-way game. Takes a lot of abuse in order to make plays.
column17: Doesn't score enough to merit a top-six forward role in the NHL. Must learn to avoid taking bad penalties--and suspensions.

column16: Has excellent scoring acumen from the back end and can run an effective power play due to a big shot and offensive instincts.
column17: Plays a very risky game, which often leads to a slew of turnovers. Must tighten up his defensive-zone coverage. Isn't very physical.

column16: Plays a sound defensive game and creates a lot of turnovers in the offensive zone. Works hard and is always hustling. Can play all three forward positions. Is good at agitating opponents.
column17: Injuries have ravaged what was once a promising two-way career. Is at times too aggressive and takes bad penalties. Doesn't have a lot of goal-scoring instincts.

column16: Has above-average playmaking skills. Is sound at both ends of the ice and displays plenty of versatility up front.
column17: Lacks the size teams look for up front. Needs ice time to produce, which limits his effectiveness on the fourth line.

column16: Was a splendid face-off man. Had terrific hand/eye coordination. Knew when and how to elevate his game when the stakes were high; he excelled in pressure situations.
column17: Not being able to stay in the lineup was his biggest detriment. Had a chronic back problem that flared up often.

column16: Has terrific playmaking ability and excellent vision. When hot, he's an  assist machine. Improved his defensive game with experience.
column17: Does not possess a knack for scoring goals, and too often will pass up a shot in the slot area. Plays a passive game and can get pushed around physically.

column16: Relies on savvy to produce points. Has above-average offensive instincts and hand/eye coordination. Possesses a heavy, accurate shot when given time to get it off.
column17: Isn't a great defensive player. His goal-scoring totals don't match his skill level, as he's never had a 30-goal campaign. Is breaking down physically over time.

column16: Plays an in-your-face style. Is effective when he keeps the game simple. Shows the ability to play with both intimidation and poise.
column17: Lacks foot speed. Is extremely limited in terms of his overall ability. Still makes a few mistakes with the puck in the defensive zone.

column16: Has excellent size. Often plays as a poor man's version of a power forward. Can play either wing or center and is also willing to stick up for teammates.
column17: Will go into prolonged scoring slumps, which hurts his ability to see greater ice time. Can take bad penalties from time to time.

column16: Has great size. Loves to play an intimidating brand of defense and land big hits in open ice. Is a great team player and popular man in the dressing room.
column17: His rugged style has made him extremely prone to both injury and suspension. Has a limited offensive game at the NHL level.

column16: Has plenty of leadership qualities, as well as grit and toughness. Owns enough experience at the NHL level to be a quality teammate in reserve.
column17: Has never been mobile enough to log important minutes along an NHL blueline. Takes a few too many dumb penalties to make a significant contribution.

column16: A strong-skating defenseman, Zalapski fit right into the NHL and was named to the league's all-rookie team in 1988-89. The Penguins' first selection (and fourth overall) in 1986 was a member of the Canadian National Team before embarking on his NHL career. Offensively gifted, he recorded a 20-goal season with the Whalers, the second of his five NHL clubs, in 1991-92.
column17: Good-sized, he didn't shy away from physical contact, but wasn't a prototypical agressive NHL backliner. Oddly, Zalapski's offensive punch began its downward slide in his late twenties, a little before expected.

column16: Excels in defensive situations, including the penalty kill. Has the size scouts love from the wing position and is an extremely industrious forward. Is a sound player without the puck.
column17: Could use his size more to punish opponents but lacks a nasty streak. Doesn't own soft hands or a goal-scorer's mentality.

column16: Is capable of playing spectacularly well for stretches and has leadership qualities as the last line of defense.
column17: Has fought consistency his entire career and is prone to going into long slumps. Over time, he has lost some of his mobility.

column16: Has a wealth of experience and solid offensive instincts. Is a dedicated professional that doesn't know the word 'quit', and a quality playmaker.
column17: Isn't the quickest forward, so he tends to struggle when the tempo of a game is moved up a notch or two. On the whole, he has average physical tools.

column16: Big and mobile, he owns soft hands that do damage around the net. Can score goals and set up his linemates. When on his game, he can dominate down low.
column17: Injuries have become a major problem. Lacks discipline and takes a lot of bad penalties in the offensive zone. Is a lazy defensive winger.

column16: Owns an excellent shot. Works very hard when on the ice. Has good scoring instincts and knows his way around the offensive zone.
column17: His skating ability prevents him from getting into scoring areas with regularity. Tends to struggle in defensive situations, which cuts into his overall value.

column16: Has speed to burn and a decent scoring touch--especially at the minor-pro level. Can play at both ends of the ice with plenty of savvy.
column17: Needs to round out his game in order to finally make the jump to the NHL. It may already be too late for that, unfortunately.

column16: Is a dependable forward at both ends of the ice. Has developed into a formidable face-off man. Can score goals in a pinch.
column17: Doesn't play with enough consistency to be a regular offensive contributor. Often shoots when a pass might have created a better scoring opportunity.

column16: Has the speed and skill to put fear in defenders every time he's in the offensive zone. Possesses a deadly accurate shot and can fire from anywhere. Is very good at beating defensemen to the outside in one-on-one situations.
column17: Isn't particularly strong on the puck and can be knocked around. His frail stature leads to frequent injuries.

column16: Can knock a talented forward off his game due to his ability to get under any opponent's skin. Is an incredible open-ice bodychecker and usually sound in the defensive zone.
column17: Is often caught out of position trying to land the big hit. Lacks an offensive dimension and is very susceptible to injury--since he always plays with reckless abandon.

column16: Likes to play a simple game from the back end. Can play on either side of the ice and rarely gets caught out of position.
column17: Has little offensive game to speak of. Does not punish you with big hits. Possesses physical attributes that seem to go to waste.

column16: Has blinding speed and good size. Excels at the forechecking game, as well as penalty-killing situations. Can score goals in bunches.
column17: Lacks consistency on offense, and his all-or-nothing style makes him an injury risk. Doesn't use his size enough to his advantage.

column16: Can log an abundance of minutes and feasts on the power play. Is extremely aggressive in the defensive zone. Has a great shot from the point and displays a lot of leadership qualities.
column17: Has a propensity to make mistakes in the defensive zone and take too many bad penalties. Can be distracted by criticism when he struggles in pressure situations.

column16: Has excellent passing skills. Plays with ice water in his veins and never gets rattled. Is extremely durable and owns an accurate point shot.
column17: Has regressed in his overall game with time. Tends to lack passion when he plays. Lacks a physical game and doesn't initiate contact with any frequency.

column16: Has a great point shot and adds an offensive dimension to any team he plays for. Skates well laterally. Is especially productive on the power play.
column17: Injuries have become a major issue over time, as he appears incapable of staying healthy for the entire season. Can get caught out of position.

column16: Is the consummate team player, since he is able to play both defense and wing. Has plenty of physical aggressiveness in his game and leadership qualities.
column17: Struggles when lined up against fleet forwards. Isn't a great pugilist, which limits his enforcer upside. Lacks consistency in his defensive game.

column16: Moves well in the crease. Has the ability to fill in after a long stretch on the bench. Is an excellent teammate.
column17: Has failed in his few attempts to earn No. 1 status in the NHL. Is too inconsistent to be given a lot of action.

column16: Owns one of the hardest point shots in the NHL. Usually keeps the game simple from the back end. Can punish forwards with hits and can also fight.
column17: Can be beaten one on one. Is a little undersized at the NHL level. His offensive production is inconsistent, as is his decision-making.

column16: Can line up at all three forward positions. Plays with poise and patience. Owns good vision and two-way smarts. Has impressive size and reach.
column17: Could stand to play more of a power game in the NHL for a greater impact. Is prone to mental lapses on the ice. Lacks natural goal-scoring ability.

column16: Has great size and is at his best when he throws it around. Extremely durable, he is an excellent two-way player and the ultimate team-first guy.
column17: Struggles with consistency in the goal-scoring department, and has become a little less aggressive over the years. Isn't an elite skater, either.

column16: Loves to hit people in open ice. Has solid two-way ability and can score at crucial points in the game.
column17: Is prone to suspensions because of occasionally dirty tactics. Is often hurt, primarily because of his kamikaze style of play. Doesn't own natural offensive skills.

column16: Has strong legs, which help him move well laterally. Owns a wealth of experience. Is effective as either a starter or backup and is a solid team player.
column17: Lacks consistency, which is why he took so long to establish himself in the NHL. Struggles sometimes with his lateral movement in the crease area.

column16: Has one of the best combinations of quickness and hands in the NHL. Is an exceptionally smooth skater. Is underrated in terms of leadership. Can still pick a corner or blow by a defenseman.
column17: Struggles when playing in a defensive system. Needs a solid playmaker on his line to excel. Has lost some of his playmaking skills over time.

column16: Blessed with a huge frame, he had a good shot and the versatility to play center and wing. Did his best work in front of the net on power plays. Also won face-offs and was a born leader.
column17: Will take bad penalties from time to time, since he has a tendency to lose his cool on the ice. His production slowed down over time, as did his wheels.

column16: Extremely talented, most observers agree that Zhamnov only scratched the tip of his potential while playing in the NHL. An outstanding skater and playmaker.
column17: Smooth Russian had more than his share of bouts with the injury bug. Not physical at all.

column16: Is a good passer and steady performer in defensive situations. Sees the ice very well. Can be effective on the power play and also play a shutdown role, due to his veteran savvy.
column17: Doesn't play a consistently physical game, especially in front of his own net. Tends to struggle more when used on the right side of the ice.

column16: Is blessed with great speed and can catch defenders off guard by blazing right by them. Has natural goal-scoring ability, good size and defensive acumen. Can play both wing and center.
column17: Still suffers through bouts of inconsistency on offense from time to time, making him somewhat streaky. Doesn't take full advantage of his size. Needs to play better in big contests.

column16: Is one of the most underrated defensemen in NHL history. Makes a consistent first pass and is a great co-pilot on the power play. Sound positioning is the secret to his success.
column17: Has never been a physical player and has lost a step over the years. Injuries limit his availability these days.

column16: Is a true franchise goalkeeper. Has an awesome combination of size and supreme command of the butterfly style. Can steal games for his team. Is a natural leader.
column17: Needs to avoid occasional lapses in concentration. Must work on better communicating with his defensemen. Isn't a very good puck-handler.

column16: Has always had enough skating ability to log regular minutes at the NHL level. Is a decent two-way defender with a decent amount of big-league experience.
column17: A lack of discipline has always been at the root of his problems at the NHL level. Makes too many mistakes to be considered a top four defenseman.

column16: Is a big presence up the middle and a good face-off man. Has above-average hands and the instincts of a natural goal-scorer. When motivated, he plays a complete game.
column17: Is a better scorer than playmaker, so he tends to get off his game when paired with other goal-scorers. His leadership skills, along with the rest of his game, lacks consistency.

column16: Displays sound positioning and the ability to get into open areas to score goals. Owns a lethal shot from the slot area and a goal-scorer's mentality.
column17: Needs to make better use of his linemates. Is woefully inconsistent. Isn't a very physical player, and he's also unable to create his own shot.

column16: Can play an electrifying, acrobatic style that leaves fans on the edge of their seat. Has the ability to win games by himself. Can play a ton of minutes and is a clutch performer.
column17: His flopping, unpredictable style makes him vulnerable against teams that go to the net hard. Can experience difficulty with rebounds. Also struggles when he over-handles the puck.

column16: Is shifty, creative, hard to knock off the puck and difficult to line up in one-on-one situations. Has smart offensive instincts.
column17: Tends to hang onto the puck too long, and still refuses to shoot the puck consistently. Is at times lackadaisical in his own end.

column16: Has great speed and defensive awareness. Can line up on either side of center and displays brief flashes of offensive brilliance. Kills penalties with aplomb. Sacrifices his body for the good of the team.
column17: His offense tends to run hot and cold, so he lacks the consistency of a legitimate scoring winger. The physical toll he pays hurts his overall production.

column16: Has great size and leadership qualities. Moves well laterally and carries a good shot from the point. Can log big minutes.
column17: Needs to be smarter, overall. Lacks the hockey sense needed to produce big offensive numbers in the NHL. Could play a more aggressive game.

column16: Has good size and plays a physical game and is reliable when he plays within his limitations. Possesses a hard, accurate point shot.
column17: Has not put up the points expected of him at the NHL level. Is inconsistent in all facets of the game. Also lacks discipline, on and off the ice.

column16: Loves to hit anything in sight. Has sound defensive instincts and is extremely aggressive in front of the net.
column17: Must differentiate between good penalties and bad penalties. Lacks offensive creativity and hockey sense, which limits his overall effectiveness.

column16: Plays well at both ends of the ice. Is capable of holding onto the puck for prolonged stretches, since he has terrific reach. Adds plenty of versatility to any roster.
column17: Is somewhat soft for a 6-3 forward, which hurts his overall NHL performance. Needs to go to the net with greater frequency to score more goals.

column16: Works hard every shift and knows how to take care of his own end. Doesn't mind playing a crash-and-bang style. Is a quality teammate.
