column17: Doesn't own top-end skating ability, which hurts his level of production. Has had trouble finding his niche in the NHL. Is too inconsistent.

column16: Has excellent hockey sense. Can score goals in bunches and excels with the man advantage. Knows how to hide from the tight checking. Possesses two-way acumen.
column17: Has always played a soft game for his 6-3, 217-pound frame. Has below-average speed, isn't getting any younger and injuries are now a factor. Can go into offensive slumps.

column16: Has the size teams look for in a blue-liner and he skates well for a big man. Is effective on either side of the ice. Can clear the front of the net.
column17: Isn't very polished in the defensive zone and prone to making bad decisions from time to time. Will at times take bad penalties that hurt his team.

column16: Has excellent hockey sense and tissue-soft hands. Loves to unleash his accurate shot from anywhere. Is also one of the league's top face-off men.
column17: Is small in stature, and his skating is a major weakness. Defensively, he can be overmatched in one-on-one battles and isn't a physical player at all.

column16: Has good size and plays a very sound, all-around game. Is versatile enough to be used in any situation and is adept at making body contact. Can come up with big goals at the right time.
column17: Can go into prolonged goal-scoring droughts that can take the rest of his game down with him. Doesn't dominate on the ice the way he could.

column16: Is shifty and hard to knock off the puck. Has great hockey sense and a fine set of hands. He's also awesome in all three zones and a tremendous back-checker.
column17: Doesn't assert himself physically enough to dominate at crunch time. Also needs to become more of a go-to player in the playoffs.

column16: Was always physically imposing. Used his size to rock opponents. Owned a rocket of a shot, which was a lethal scoring weapon for him. Logged a lot of low-maintenance minutes and was born to lead.
column17: At times, he tried for the big hit when it was not necessary. Had injury problems at various times in his career.

column16: Has good size at 6-1, 225 pounds and uses it effectively to play a tight defensive game. Is able to combine a physical defensive game with discipline. Can log a ton of minutes and is a leader.
column17: Won't put up big offensive numbers, which is partly due to the fact he doesn't take a lot of shots from the point. Is somewhat limited in terms of natural ability.

column16: Knows how to handle the physical game and is a natural leader. Will pay the price to score goals and also has sound defensive qualities.
column17: Is not a natural finisher, and will occasionally miss easy scoring chances. Has to avoid taking bad penalties. His physical style can lead to injury.

column16: Loves to see plenty of action and thrives as a starter in short spurts. Plays with the swagger of a veteran and can make spectacular saves.
column17: Has had trouble adjusting to a backup role at the NHL level. Could use more fluidity in his lateral movement. Needs to accept his limitations.

column16: Is usually a plus player and combines leadership with a good shot from the point and hockey sense. Plays with a mean streak. Always thinks team first.
column17: Takes a few too many bad penalties that can hurt his team. Tends to lose control of his temper. Lacks offensive flair. Is wearing down over time.

column16: Had solid puck-moving skills, plus on-ice vision and poise. He also possessed an accurate shot and tons of savvy.
column17: Had lost a step and was no longer a major scoring option from the back end in later years. Could get knocked around in the defensive zone.

column16: Has tremendous size for the wing position and sound defensive instincts. Is an intimidating presence on the ice.
column17: Needs to improve his skating stride in order to play regularly at the NHL level. Doesn't own high-end scoring skills.

column16: Can score goals in bunches and owns a howitzer of a shot. Is adept at playing the point on power plays, and can line up on either side of center. Has size and sound offensive instincts.
column17: Needs to play with more consistency and focus on his play without the puck, since he tends to take shifts off. Can go into deep scoring droughts. Lacks physicality.
column18: Inconsistent winger with a big shot

column16: Demonstrates good work ethic and doesn't shy away from anyone--despite his small stature. Has solid leadership skills. Can log a lot of ice time.
column17: Doesn't produce enough points. Has trouble handling big forwards in front of the net. Will always be under constant scrutiny because of his small frame.

column16: Has a great combination of size and two-way savvy. Displays decent hands and a mean streak. Is solid on face-offs and sound defensively.
column17: Has questionable hockey sense, which limits him in the scoring department. Isn't as complete a player as his package suggests.

column16: Is a classic overachiever and his motor never stops running. Can play any style needed and is an excellent team player.
column17: May not score a lot at the NHL level, so he needs more work on the little things that help win hockey games. Is only an average skater and lacks size.

column16: Has great speed, excellent playmaking ability and durability--despite his lack of size. Generally plays a sound two-way game.
column17: Tends to wear down physically because of his smallish stature. Needs to find his niche at the NHL level.

column16: Has the skill, smarts and grit to compensate for a lack of size. Can produce good numbers in streaks. Can play through a lot of pain.
column17: Lacks the ideal size of a true No. 1 center. Needs to play with more game-to-game consistency. Tends to wear down physically.

column16: Has good size, excellent strength, a deceptive shot and adequate quickness for a big man. Plays with a chip on his shoulder on most nights.
column17: Hasn't shown much of a scoring touch in the pro game, as opposed to his stellar junior career. Takes bad penalties from time to time.

column16: Big, strong and versatile forward was primarily known for his defensive brilliance but could also help out on offense during his prime years thanks to yeoman's work. Never recorded a 20-goal campaign in the NHL yet came close on a handful of occasions. Signed as a free agent by the expansion Tampa Bay Lightning in 1992, he captained the same club later in 1998-99. A career highlight proved to be his participation as a member of Team Canada in the 1998 Olympics.
column17: Not the fleetest of skaters and didn't have a dangerous shot or nifty hands, the rugged forward also ran into his share of injuries.

column16: Can easily get opponents off their game. Is a good open-ice hitter. A fairly quick skater, he defends his own end effectively and is an excellent penalty-killer. Is versatile enough to play on either side of center.
column17: Despite his dedication, he doesn't have the size or skill level to be a major scorer. Is somewhat prone to taking bad penalties and doesn't always time his big hits correctly.

column16: Has all the physical tools every organization looks for in a top defenseman. Usually plays his best against top forwards. Can fill in on the power-play point and excels on the penalty kill.
column17: Doesn't make an impact with his physicality, despite his 6-2, 209-pound frame. Can be somewhat erratic at times with the puck on his stick.

column16: Has good size and strength in fighting off players in the corners. Owns a deceptively quick shot and skating ability. Is extremely determined and feisty. Will drop the gloves if need be.
column17: Though he's determined and gutsy, he often loses a lot of fights. Is miscast when playing on one of the top three lines. Will take bad penalties when provoked.

column16: Is not afraid of laying on the body, despite his smallish frame. Does his best work when aggravating opponents. Possesses some offensive ability.
column17: May not survive playing his ultra-aggressive style in the NHL, at only 5-11, 190 pounds. Must start showing more consistency in all aspects of the game.

column16: Is an extremely gifted offensive talent. Has plenty of creativity and intelligence with the puck. Owns outstanding mobility and confidence. Can also dish out hits.
column17: Can get easily knocked off the puck at the NHL level. His work in the defensive zone, and without the puck in general, can use some tightening up. Isn't a consistent hitter.
column18: Power play quarterback and rushing defenseman

column16: Is very sound defensively and does the little things that win hockey games. Complements talented forwards. Is good in front of the opposing goal. Possesses a great slap shot.
column17: Is prone to prolonged slumps and is not a natural goal-scorer. His shots often miss the target and he has become injury-prone with advanced age.

column16: Has excellent strength and reach. Is extremely slick, loves to find the holes and has a wide variety of shots. Consistency is the name of his game.
column17: While strong on his skates, he's not overly physical despite impressive size. Is showing signs of decay and becoming more prone to injury with time.

column16: Displays good overall ability and hockey sense. Has the talent to contribute on the power play.
column17: Is undersized for the blueline position and has a tendency to get pushed around in the defensive zone.

column16: Plays a solid, up-and-down style and skates well. Cycles the puck down low with authority and loves to hit people. Always puts his team first.
column17: Lacks the touch around the net needed to see more ice time at the NHL level. After several lost bouts and concussion problems, he's no longer much of a fighter.

column16: Journeyman defenseman managed to play more than 500 games in the NHL. Mobile, Zettler's above-average skating ability was used mainly to patrol the defensive zone. Provided excellent blueline depth throughout his NHL tenure.
column17: Limited in terms of offensive skills and not a banger by any means, two key qualities that most No. 4-5 defensemen pack.

column16: Works very hard every shift. Is a solid penalty-killer and face-off man. Has the size and defensive acumen to shut down offensive forwards.
column17: Has never been able to translate AHL production into regular point production at the highest level. Lacks consistency in the offensive zone.

column16: Loves to initiate contact. Holds his own in five-on-five competition and is unafraid of dropping the gloves. Throws opponents off their game with antics.
column17: Does a bit too much trash-talking on the ice and occasionally hurts his team by taking bad penalties. Is extremely injury-prone.

column16: Has quickness, soft hands, very good hand/eye coordination, intelligence and puck savvy. Is always willing to shoot the puck from anywhere.
column17: His smallish stature has indirectly led to concussion problems over time. Also has difficulty playing within a strict defensive system.

column16: Has good size and speed. Is most effective when used in a checking role, since he plays better when given specific tasks. Owns versatility.
column17: Never developed into the big scorer his draft position suggested. Struggles to find any consistency in all aspects of the game of hockey.

column16: Has good size for a goalkeeper. Is mature beyond his years and has excelled at every level he's played regularly.
column17: Must start making some NHL noise soon. May be limited to backup duties in the big league, unless he becomes a more consistent performer.

column16: A great face-off man and two-way center, he excels in penalty-killing situations. Has smart passing skills, is a born leader and inspirational teammate.
column17: Is not a major goal-scoring threat. Doesn't have a lot of natural ability, and needs to work extra hard night after night. Is on the decline in terms of production.

column16: Has great imagination with the puck and the hands to score plenty of goals. Shoots the puck from anywhere on the ice and owns a bit of a mean streak.
column17: Needs to add even more strength in order to thrive against NHL defenders. Takes foolish penalties on occasion, and a few too many nights off.

column16: Sees the ice well. Makes sharp passes out of the defensive zone. Is poised and a good skater. Blocks shots and uses his smarts to fend off forwards.
column17: Doesn't use his 6-2, 204-pound frame nearly enough and lacks physical presence. Is not considered much of an offensive threat.

column16: Has great mobility and intelligence from behind the blue-line. Can put up points at lower levels and be used on the power play if need be.
column17: Is a little undersized for the NHL level, and he also lacks a consistent physical dimension to his game. Doesn't use his offensive gifts enough at the highest level.

column16: Moved the puck up the ice well, had a good point shot, and capably dished out punishment when needed be.
column17: Injury-prone, which curtailed his ability to produce big numbers at the highest level. Lacked defensive polish.

column16: Has exceptional vision and creativity on the ice. His offensive instincts are off the charts and he also likes to agitate.
column17: Still needs a lot of work in the defensive zone. Lacks bulk and is quite undersized by NHL standards. Isn't much of a goal-scorer.

column16: Possesses a high skill level, good skating ability and an extremely accurate shot from the point. Reads the ice well and has a very sound work ethic.
column17: Is not a physical player at all and relies solely on positioning to stop opposing forwards. While he's worked on his defensive game over the years, it's still mediocre.

column16: Can handle the puck effectively and is strong in his own end. Uses his size well and has a defensive conscience. Is capable of shutting down offensive centers.
column17: A lack of any one dominant skill could ultimately prove to be his undoing. Doesn't have the offensive upside to be a productive center.

column16: Owns an infectious attitude and never stops his motor while on the ice. Plays a crash-and-bang game and is a willing combatant. Always thinks team-first.
column17: Lacks skill and must work doubly hard for every point he earns. Is prone to taking bad penalties from time to time.

column16: Is great on the forecheck and can kill penalties with aplomb. Owns good speed and is extremely tenacious. Has excellent two-way ability. Also possesses a great shot.
column17: While capable of scoring, he's not a go-to guy on offense because he lacks consistency in that department. His rambunctious style can lead to injuries.

column16: Uses his size well, especially in the offensive zone, and likes to create space for his linemates. Has a terrific shot and is defensively responsible. Can log important minutes.
column17: Hasn't lived up to offensive expectations and is prone to inconsistency. Lacks ideal playmaking skills from the center position.

column16: Possesses tremendous defensive instincts. Is extremely strong in the corners. Has excellent hockey sense. Is willing to play through pain and displays good leadership qualities.
column17: Is rather mediocre on offense. Isn't great at beating defenders one-on-one. His gung-ho style of play can often lead to several injuries. Doesn't have a goal-scorer's mentality, nor the hands to do so regularly.

column16: Has speed to burn and a wealth of experience at lower levels. Plays a sound game in the defensive zone and is a solid teammate.
column17: Never lived up to expectations, after being selected sixth overall in 1995. Lacks hockey sense and offensive creativity.

column16: Was an excellent penalty-killer and good skater. Knew how to take opposing players off their game. Worked hard and provided leadership to his team.
column17: Was a limited point producer at the height of his career, and eventually his offense was almost non-existent. Would occasionally take bad penalties.

column16: Has a strong reputation for his penalty-killing, checking and leadership ability. Is still a great skater and can line up at all three forward positions.
column17: Doesn't have great hands and lacks the confidence to consistently finish off plays. Isn't big and tends to wear down over the course of an 82-game schedule.

column16: Has blinding speed, which he uses effectively to check opponents. Is versatile enough to play any position and fill in anywhere in the lineup. Displays sound defensive ability and is a good penalty-killer.
column17: Has a lot of difficulty finding the back of the net on a regular basis, and goes through lengthy scoring droughts. Has a propensity to get hurt because of his all-out hustle.

column16: Has a shooter's touch and loads of deception to his game. Is very good on breakaways and versatile enough to play either wing position.
column17: Tends to get lazy at times. Doesn't use his size nearly enough. When not scoring goals, his game goes into the tank.

column16: Has underrated playmaking skills. Goes to the net with ample vigor and scores the majority of his goals due to supreme determination.
column17: His style of play often leads to serious injuries. Doesn't have enough of a shot to be an elite goal-scoring winger.

column16: Is bullish in the offensive zone and causes turnovers. Has great size and uses it effectively. Displays a sound defensive game and streaky scoring ability.
column17: Lacks skating speed. Has a tendency to take too many bad penalties, which often affects his ice time. Can go into long scoring slumps. Is prone to injury.

column16: Sees the ice extremely well. His passing game is among the best in the NHL. Possesses shiftiness and tenacity. Can make his linemates better players. Is a leader.
column17: Has had trouble remaining healthy towards the latter part of his career, which has slowed down production. Is below average in the goal-scoring department and prone to slumps.
column18: Aging, yet versatile playmaker on his last legs

column16: Possesses terrific vision and passing skills. Also features outstanding speed, puck-handling ability and agitating qualities.
column17: Needs talented scorers on his line in order to maximize his gifts. Doesn't play a physical game and lacks the strength to dominate.

column16: Is big, strong and loves to punish people with body checks. Has learned to play within his limitations. Displays excellent leadership qualities.
column17: Has always been a below-average skater and runs into trouble keeping up with the flow of the game on occasion.

column16: Is a mountain of a man and displays a big-time mean streak. Could be a major asset for any NHL club if used judiciously.
column17: Needs work on his skating, especially the quick pivot. Is extremely limited in terms of his offensive capability. Can't log big minutes.

column16: Displays terrific hockey sense. Skates very well, is fearless and can log a ton of ice time. Can also play a physical game, despite his lack of size.
column17: Doesn't put up the offensive totals expected of him. Tends to struggle with consistency issues in all areas of the game. Has become more prone to injury over time.

column16: Has a wealth of experience. Is extremely agile. Usually controls his rebounds with aplomb. Just when you think he's down and out, he makes a miraculous stop.
column17: Gets into odd funks whenever he plays too deep in his net. Has never been very good at handling the puck. Can he adjust to a backup role to end his career?

column16: Is extremely fast on skates and has terrific penalty-killing skills. Can set up his linemates or take the play to the outside with aplomb. Is an offensive threat when short-handed.
column17: Is not a great goal-scorer and tends to go into prolonged scoring droughts. More was expected of him, but he was not able to reach his offensive potential.

column16: Likes to play a north-south game and is strong along the wall. Defensively responsible, he's also a great leader in the room.
column17: Has limited scoring ability at the NHL level. While he's always willing, his pugilistic skills leave a lot to be desired.

column16: Has blinding speed and is a tenacious forechecker. Likes to get physical and play an energy role. Can play either center or left wing. Is a good face-off man.
column17: Lacks offensive flair and struggles to put points on the board. Is also somewhat injury-prone and lacking in physical toughness.

column16: Played a consistently rugged brand of hockey. Always led by example and scored big goals when it counted most.
column17: Injuries were a factor throughout his career.

column16: Has good size and excellent defensive instincts. Skates well and is versatile enough to play anywhere up front.
column17: Has underachieved on offense, mainly because of prolonged scoring droughts and a lack of offensive instincts.

column9: Usti nad Labem, Czech. (now Czech Republic)
column16: Has excellent hands, as well as the instincts to find open ice. Knows how to make himself invisible in the offensive zone. Can unleash an ultra-quick shot at a moment's notice.
column17: His small, light frame is a target for the opposition's most physical players. Nowadays, he struggles with defensive-zone coverage. Tends to wear down as the season rolls along.

column16: Has great size for the goaltending position. Plays with poise and lets the puck hit him. Can fill in as a starting netminder from time to time.
column17: Doesn't have No. 1 goaltender ability, mainly because of a lack of consistency. Needs more work on his lateral mobility.

column16: Was extremely tenacious on the forecheck. Had excellent defensive skills and also killed penalties very efficiently. Could line up anywhere up front.
column17: After putting up good numbers in college and in the AHL, his scoring touch disappeared. Didn't have enough bulk in order to thrive in the corners.

column16: Is a responsible two-way player with a great work ethic. Has shown a nose for the net, especially at the AHL level.
column17: Still needs to add strength if he intends to raise his game to another level. Has a great shot but doesn't produce enough with it.

column16: Has a tremendous attitude and can inspire teammates with his work ethic. Displays good two-way instincts and has produced in the minor-pro ranks.
column17: Is limited in overall talent. Will always have to work his tail off just to keep his NHL job.

column16: Has excellent playmaking skills and vision. Is as creative as they come in the offensive zone. Can play any forward position.
column17: Must get stronger and continue to work on the little things in order to play regularly in the NHL, since his game lacks versatility and refinement.

column16: Is one of the most natural blue-line talents in the NHL in terms of his skill-set. Has size, physical aggression and strength. Can also quarterback a power play.
column17: Tends to be out of position from time to time, leading to odd-man rushes against his team. Has already peaked as an offensive rearguard. Will also take bad penalties that hurt his team.

column16: Is mobile and moves the puck quickly and efficiently out of the defensive zone. Has the size every NHL scout looks for in a blue-liner.
column17: Doesn't use his size effectively enough. Doesn't put up good enough offensive numbers to see regular power play minutes. Is prone to errors.

column16: Can play a tough brand of hockey but is also smart and reliable. Uses his size well is rarely caught out of position. Kills penalties with aplomb.
column17: Lacks offensive flair. Rarely leads the rush or head-mans the puck up ice. Isn't great at pinching in from the point, either. Injuries are an issue.

column16: Can play both center or wing. Has a history of point production in the minor leagues. Is effective when used judiciously.
column17: Isn't big or fast enough to play top-six forward minutes in the NHL. Has not parlayed minor-league success into big-league points.

column16: Is very athletic in the goal crease. Makes the spectacular save look routine. Shakes off bad goals well. Plays with the intensity of a power forward.
column17: Consistency has always eluded him at the NHL level. Has trouble with long shots. Will give up untimely goals.

column16: The consummate team player, he never complained when asked to move to defense (or back to his natural forward position). He was a true speed demon from the back end. Versatility was the key to his game.
column17: Lacked the bulk needed to thrive as a defenseman. Sometimes, he struggled to pick up the finer points of playing defense. Wasn't a high scorer at the highest level.

column16: Is an excellent penalty-killer and tenacious checker versus offensive forwards. Brings energy to the lineup every shift. Is a threat to score while short-handed and a born leader.
column17: Doesn't put up the consistent numbers needed to play on a scoring line. Plays with reckless abandon, which can sometimes lead to injury. Has started to wear down physically.

column16: Possesses the total package: Speed, incredible defensive qualities, terrific hands and great passing skills. Has matured into a savvy veteran.
column17: Injuries are starting to take a toll on his body. Will at times go through the motions and not play with enough desire and grit. His point totals are in decline.

column16: When he's on his game, his positioning and technique are nearly flawless. Has an athletic build and a positive attitude.
column17: Can be beaten upstairs. Needs to improve the mental aspects of the game in order to improve. Lets in the odd soft goal.

column16: Does his best work in front of the opposing goal and along the boards. Is very capable on special teams and as a checker, is extremely durable and can score in bunches.
column17: Has to work extra hard for his goals, since he lacks top-end speed. Despite his mammoth frame, he doesn't play with nasty intentions.

column16: Has excellent hockey sense, a deceptive shot and natural scoring instincts. Is at his best when playmaking from the wing position.
column17: Lacks size and strength, and can be easily pushed off the puck. Tends to go long stretches without scoring goals.

column16: Is extremely industrious, tough and usually disciplined. Can score big goals and plays a strong two-way game. Has excellent leadership skills.
column17: Isn't the big-time scorer he once was as a junior player. Does not make his presence known as often as he needs to.

column16: Is sound defensively, plays well within a system and is a great team player. Has excellent hitting ability and can also protect his teammates.
column17: Has always had trouble staying healthy. Will occasionally take bad penalties. Doesn't score a lot. Off-ice issues have also hurt his career.

column16: Shows good poise and positional play. Has a decent point shot and puts up points as a result. Owns the size NHL scouts look for in a defenseman.
column17: Needs to avoid injuries, which have been a major factor in his career. Must use his size more effectively in order to make more of an impact. More grit would help his game overall.

column16: Is a supreme penalty-killer and, when healthy, one of the best checking-line centers in the NHL. Possesses excellent team qualities.
column17: Is an extremely injury-prone player. Lacks offensive ability at the NHL level.

column16: Has good mobility for his impressive size. Can quickly move the puck up ice. Owns a wealth of savvy and experience.
column17: Doesn't use his big body effectively enough. Can at times make costly errors in the defensive zone that hurt his team.

column16: Has excellent defensive skills and is hard to knock off the puck. Is a solid team player and quality professional.
column17: Won't ever pile up big numbers in the NHL. Needs to find his niche so as to remain in the big league for the long haul.

column16: Uses his intelligence to dominate the game. Has an incredibly accurate shot from the point. Is very efficient in the defensive zone. Thrives with lots of ice time. Is a great lateral skater.
column17: Is not a physical player by any stretch of the imagination. Has started to wear down because of years of logging tons of ice time.

column16: Has good skating ability, a great shot from the point and an all-around performer along the blueline. Is also a premier body-checking rearguard.
column17: Isn't a natural power-play quarterback and is inconsistent on offense. Gets out of position on occasion in an attempt to make the big hit.

column16: When at his best, he plays it safe and tough in the defensive zone. Is good at clearing the front of the net.
column17: Must limit mistakes in the defensive zone, since he doesn't have the talent to recover quickly. Has a virtually non-existent offensive game.

column16: Has excellent size for the goaltending position and is capable of shutting the door even when cold. Is a dedicated and persistent athlete.
column17: Is vulnerable to low shots and his reflexes aren't up to NHL standards. Consistency has always eluded him at the highest level.

column16: Had both size and physical presence along the blue-line. Could play a solid team game when he kept it simple. Thrived on the penalty kill. Added leadership to any dressing room.
column17: Lacked consistency and a little confidence from time to time. Didn't always make the right decision in the defensive zone. Had become injury-prone with advanced age.

column16: Usually plays in control of his emotions, so he never lets bad goals bother him. Bounces back as good as any goalie in the NHL. Is an excellent team player.
column17: Still lets in soft goals on occasion and can lose his fundamentals from time to time. Has always had trouble with long shots.

column16: Has plenty of hockey smarts and a wealth of playmaking ability. Is a proven scorer at lower levels.
column17: Is smallish and brittle, which makes it difficult for him to find regular playing time at the NHL level. Must improve his defensive game.

column16: Has terrific speed and energy. Is solid on the forecheck and good at killing penalties. Can score goals in bunches.
column17: Has shown very little consistency in the offensive zone throughout his NHL career. His gung-ho style can lead to injuries.

column16: Is one of the fastest skaters in the NHL, which continues to make him a threat on the ice. Usually raises his level of play come playoff time.
column17: Has not lived up to offensive expectations. Can be lazy at times. Is too streaky in terms of production.

column16: Has great vision on the ice, imposing size and imagination with the puck. Can play all three forward positions. Is outstanding in the shootout.
column17: Has fought the inconsistency bug throughout his time in the NHL, which explains his constant moving from team to team. Doesn't play a physical game.

column16: Was one of the best passers and most intelligent players ever to play the game. Had terrific poise and leadership skills, as well.
column17: Was never much of a goal-scoring threat, mainly because his shot was below average. Was also smallish and somewhat fragile.

column16: Has size, strength and a big-time mean streak. Plays with a chip on his shoulder, which makes him an effective NHL enforcer.
column17: Has a lot to work to do on his skating. Isn't a very good defensive player and shouldn't be counted on to play more than a handful of shifts per game.

column16: Skates well, and oozes offensive creativity and puck poise. Owns a wealth of experience at all levels. Is solid at both ends of the ice.
column17: Is small for the NHL game, which was the main reason he didn't meet expectations in his first go-around. Plays a passive game.

column16: Is adept at clearing the front of the net and strong in defensive situations. Displays a nice combination of toughness and leadership.
column17: Needs to play within his limits on a consistent basis. At times, his decision-making in the defensive zone leaves a lot to be desired. Doesn't have a lot of offensive ability.

column16: Is a huge presence and displays terrific defensive instincts and leadership. Possesses a decent shot from the point. Loves the challenge of shutting opponents down.
column17: Offensively, he is pretty much limited to his shot so he gets into trouble when trying to do too much with the puck. Is a little inconsistent in the hitting department.

column16: Has elusive moves. Plays well coming down his off-wing and likes to set up from the side of the net on the power play. Anticipates the play well.
column17: Will always be small and light, which makes him susceptible to losing battles down low. Still needs more work in the defensive zone.

column16: Has one of the hardest point shots in the league. Reads the ice well and knows when to jump into the play. Is solid in his own end and has big-league size.
column17: His durability is constantly questioned and staying healthy is always an issue. Isn't very physical, despite being 6-3, 215 pounds.
column18: Fragile all-around defenseman with a big shot

column16: Is a solid stand-up goaltender. Plays his angles well and controls his rebounds efficiently. Has good size at 6-1, which suits his style perfectly.
column17: Has yet to dominate at any level, which makes him far from a certain No. 1 goaltender down the road. Couples good games with below-average starts.

column16: Has a good combination of passing and shooting skills from the point. Is a good-sized defender with sound mobility.
column17: Doesn't always play with optimum intensity. Should make better use of his 6-2, 205-pound frame, since he is at times a little too soft.

column16: Has supreme offensive skills. Is a great passer and dangerous point man on the power play. Can handle heavy workloads at the highest level.
column17: Doesn't always commit to playing defense and is a major liability in his own zone. Needs a defensive defenseman beside him to cover for his mistakes.

column16: Is positionally sound and he uses his big reach to defend in his own end. Displays a lot of hockey sense.
column17: Injuries destroyed the tail end of his career, as he was unable to utilize his massive frame to the best of his ability.

column16: Possesses tremendous hockey smarts and the ability to find his teammates with excellent passes. A good skater, he loves to join the attack.
column17: Still makes occasional mistakes when pinching in. Could use more strength to better handle big NHL forwards. Doesn't shoot enough.

column16: Has the ability to bounce back after a shaky game. Accepts his role and is a solid team player.
column17: Lacks the consistency needed to win a regular job in the NHL. Is prone to giving up untimely goals.

column16: Hits everything that moves, and likes to antagonize opponents. Never backs down from a challenge and always gives maximum effort on the ice. Is a solid team player.
column17: Will at times take bad penalties that set his team back. Has a limited scoring touch. Doesn't always win fights against the league's top pugilists.

column16: Can come up with spectacular saves from out of nowhere. Never quits on a play, and never gets too down on himself when he struggles. Is a good team player.
column17: Is prone to brain cramps with the puck, since he doesn't handle it well. When he's off his game, he can get shelled due to a lack of textbook form in goal.

column16: Has deceptive speed, great strength and a lethal shot. Can overpower defenders physically or use finesse. Possesses the soft hands of a natural goal-scorer, but will also drop the gloves when necessary.
column17: Is needed on the ice, so he's limited in the amount of physical toughness he can display. Needs good players around him to produce numbers at peak levels.

column16: Is versatile enough in all aspects of the game to play wherever needed. Leads by example. Has the wheels to be an offensive threat.
column17: Frustrates many with his lack of offensive consistency. While he's played his best hockey in the postseason, he doesn't play at that level all the time.

column16: Is one of the fastest hockey players currently toiling in the pro game. Can burn defensemen with his skating ability. Has a sturdy frame to handle traffic and can line up anywhere up front.
column17: Lacks hockey sense, which prevents him from making it big in the NHL. Needs to learn how to play at different speeds. Doesn't have enough confidence in his offensive ability.

column16: Is an exceptional skater, and he excels when killing penalties. Sees the ice well and loves to use his imagination. Has solid defensive instincts and versatility.
column17: Has battled several injuries over the course of his career, and is somewhat fragile. Could use a few more pounds in order to do a better job in the corners.
column18: Very good, yet fragile two-way winger

column16: His defensive ability is beyond reproach. Has exceptional hockey sense. Always knows where to be on the ice and displays an excellent attitude. Can score goals in the clutch.
column17: Plays a soft game in the corners and can get pushed off the puck with relative ease. Has never put it all together in the offensive zone. Is injury-prone.

column16: Has the ability to work the boards and a knack for delivering thunderous hits. Is an excellent forechecker and knows when to pressure the puck-carrier.
column17: Has had an extensive injury history. Isn't offensively gifted and needs to work extremely hard for every point he earns.

column16: Is extremely gifted, including speed, versatility, the ability to hold onto the puck for long stretches, great passing skills and tremendous one-on-one moves.
column17: Doesn't have a lot of strength to combat big NHL defenders in the corners. Doesn't shoot the puck enough, which leads to mediocre goal-scoring totals.

column16: His combination of speed, skill and size makes him very hard to contain. Knows how to find the back of the net and also possesses outstanding defensive skills.
column17: Is vulnerable in highly physical contests. Has never scored more than 93 points in an NHL regular season, despite all-world ability.

column16: Excels on face-offs and all defensive situations, especially on the penalty kill. Has good size for the pivot position. Displays leadership qualities and a sound work ethic.
column17: Has limited scoring and/or playmaking ability. Also doesn't have the greatest skating stride, which limits his ice time in the NHL.

column16: Has exceptional speed, which rivals that of the majority of NHL pivots. Works hard in all three zones. Can win important face-offs.
column17: Has a tendency to get hurt. Doesn't use his 6-2 frame enough to his advantage. Should produce more points but lacks consistency in that department.

column16: Is an accomplished defensive forward. Has good size, speed, leadership qualities and face-off ability. Can play any forward position.
column17: Has not met offensive expectations. Lacks both confidence and polish in the offensive zone. Doesn't shoot the puck nearly enough.

column16: Uses his size effectively and has a mean streak. Possesses a good shot from the point and decent skills. Is a true leader in every way.
column17: His mean streak can sometimes get the best of him and he can be prone to taking bad penalties. Lacks mobility and can get burned to the outside.

column16: Has excellent size for the goaltending position and the ability to come off the bench at the highest level. Also displays good team qualities.
column17: Has battled consistency issues in the pro ranks. Lacks the quickness to excel at the National Hockey League level.

column16: Possesses tremendous reach, excellent vision and creativity. Skates very well for a 6-4 center. Has good hand/eye coordination and a winning attitude.
column17: Can go into scoring funks from time to time. Will occasionally drop the gloves, which penalizes his team more because he's needed on the ice.

column16: Is a rock solid, stay-at-home defenseman. Contains opposing forwards and can play a physical brand of hockey.
column17: Isn't the most mobile defender and can be hurt to the outside. Persistent knee and back problems have dogged him throughout his career. Will occasionally take dumb penalties.

column16: Excels in defensive situations. Is a very gifted skater and makes solid outlet passes. Has a good shot that can be somewhat effective on the power play.
column17: Is not a natural puck-handler, so he's not power-play quarterback material. Doesn't use his to physically intimidate opponents.

column16: Is a physical presence, and can do some damage to onrushing forwards in open ice. Blocks shots very effectively.
column17: Tends to wear down over the course of a long season. Doesn't have a lot of offensive upside. Still makes glaring mistakes in his own end.

column16: Moves the puck well out of the defensive zone. Has an excellent frame and displays plenty of poise from the back end.
column17: Doesn't use his size effectively enough to be a factor along the blue-line most nights. Lacks consistency in all aspects of the game.

column16: Covers the net well. Plays with poise and confidence. Handles the puck like a defenseman. Is improving in the mental aspects of goaltending.
column17: Still lacks the consistency needed to play the starter's role at the NHL level. Will he ever take his game to another level?

column16: Plays a smooth, poised style and also displays solid hitting skills. Has savvy offensive acumen. Can be used in all situations and log a ton of ice time.
column17: Isn't considered a power-play quarterback. Doesn't punish people in the Scott Stevens-Derian Hatcher mold. Is prone to getting hurt.

column16: Plays a smart positional game and shows good two-way instincts. Has speed and is an accomplished defensive player--especially while killing penalties.
column17: Lacks a physical edge, despite his 6-2 frame. Needs to be able to grind it out better along the boards. Is capable of scoring more goals, but doesn't.

column16: Keeps things simple and tidy in the defensive zone. Uses his size effectively against skilled forwards. Knows when to pinch in from the point.
column17: Is inconsistent on offense, which runs hot and cold, and isn't a natural power play quarterback.

column16: Sees the ice incredibly well. Has terrific hand/eye coordination, good goal-scoring instincts and excellent puck-distribution skills. Can play all three forward positions.
column17: Is somewhat soft in the corners and can be accused of playing a peripheral game at times. Has become more prone to injury over time.

column16: Owns a big shot from the point, as well as a wealth of International experience. He's also mobile for his size.
column17: Has always had issues in the defensive zone. Doesn't utilize his 6-2, 200-plus-pound frame to his advantage.

column16: Has a strong lower body and isn't afraid to use it in the corners. Plays an aggressive style but is also defensive responsible.
column17: Lacks top-end talent and will have to find a niche as a defensive forward in order to make it at the NHL level.

column16: Is extremely energetic and an excellent two-way forward. Can play either wing position and possesses great speed. Has enough versatility to play defense in emergency situations.
column17: Lacks consistency on offense; he can go very long stretches without scoring. His smallish frame is a hindrance in forechecking situations. Concussions are a real problem for him.

column16: Loves to block shots and defend against top forwards. Has great character and an infectious personality. Is underrated with the puck.
column17: Has limited offensive capability. Doesn't play with as much physicality as he used to.

column16: Has great size and moves the puck well. Is effective when used judiciously.
column17: Must keep the defensive turnovers to a minimum and increase his physical presence behind the blueline. Has battled injuries throughout his career.

column16: Has a good shot, size and two-way ability. Plays a solid game in all three zones. Understands the positioning aspects of the game of hockey. Can play the point on power plays.
column17: Doesn't always use his size to gain an advantage over his opponents. Could stand to play with a bit more grit and enthusiasm. Has limitations as a passer and playmaker.

column16: Is athletic and positionally sound most of the time. Owns a positive attitude, which rubs off on his teammates.
column17: Can lose focus and give up soft goals, which has ruined a promising career. Is largely a goaltender in decline, mainly because of a suspect mental game.

column16: Plays with a lot of aggression and is effective in a crash-and-bang setting. Is not intimidated by anyone.
column17: Is extremely limited in offensive situations. Lacks the skating ability needed to play regularly in the NHL.

column16: Has great size and all-around upside. Can move the puck out of danger efficiently. Plays with poise.
column17: Gets himself caught out of position on occasion and makes the wrong play at the wrong time. Needs to use his size more.

column16: Has a massive body and excellent pugilistic skills. Can play an intimidating role whenever he's on the ice.
column17: Still has to learn the intricacies of playing the wing position. Lacks skating ability. Is extremely undisciplined.

column16: Has great hockey sense, plus good mobility, a heavy point shot and a long reach to defend attacking forwards. Is efficient when playing the man.
column17: His physical intensity isn't always where it needs to be to keep opposing forwards honest. Is not a high-end offensive producer from the back end.

column16: Had the entire physical package -- size, skill and skating ability -- to be an asset along an NHL blueline. Over time, he gained valuable experience on how to play in North America, but never at the level he was expected to when drafted second overall in 1996.
column17: Suffered from adaptation problems early in his NHL career. Lacked consistency in both his decision-making and defensive-zone coverage, at times resulting in ill-timed blunders.

column16: Skates like the wind and is a tireless forechecker. Can play all three forward positions. Is a sound performer in the defensive zone.
column17: Plays more of a peripheral game and doesn't initiate a lot of contact. Lacks the finish needed to find the back of the net on a consistent basis.

column16: Possesses the hands of a surgeon and knowledge of where to go to score goals. Pays the price in front of the net in order to light the lamp.
column17: Has a tendency to go into scoring slumps. Isn't always a consistent worker for 60 minutes. Needs to use his big frame more to his advantage.

column16: Has the size teams look for up front. Can play effectively at any forward position. Is a sound hitter in all three zones.
column17: Needs refinement in all areas of the game. While his overall package is impressive, he does not make the most of his physical gifts.

column16: Has better-than-average offensive ability. Possesses a hard shot from the point and solid power-play instincts. Also owns a mean streak.
column17: Needs more polish in the defensive aspects of the game. Must show more intensity and maturity on a regular basis.

column16: Has sound checking ability and plays with tremendous energy and grit. Uses his body effectively and is incredibly versatile in defensive situations.
column17: Is not a big goal-scorer, since his hands are below average. His work ethic has led to plenty of injury trouble throughout his NHL career.

column16: Usually plays a safe game from the back end. Owns thunderous body-checking ability and defensive poise. Has the potential to dominate a game physically.
column17: Has a tendency to overhandle the puck from time to time. Can also be a little too aggressive at times, which places his team in trouble.

column16: Has a huge frame and knows how to use it to protect the puck. Owns defensive awareness and the versatility to play any role on a hockey team. Can also play all three forward positions.
column17: Never lived up to advanced billing as a scorer. Doesn't give an all-out effort every night. Lacks consistency and confidence with the puck. Also doesn't shoot the puck nearly enough.

column16: Can be an imposing figure, with his combination of size and speed. Has an NHL-caliber shot and a tendency to use it frequently.
column17: Hasn't been able to put it all together at the NHL level. Tends to fight the puck at times. Has been beset by injuries.

column16: Can log a ton of ice time without issue. Is a well-liked teammate in the locker room. Displays all-around prowess. Can play a nasty game from behind the blue-line from time to time.
column17: Can at times make bad decisions with the puck in the defensive zone. Is also known to take a few undisciplined penalties from time to time.

column16: Is an intelligent player that is most effective checking opposing centers. Has sound hockey sense and pretty good passing ability.
column17: Could use his body a little more effectively against offensive pivots. Will never be confused with a great goal-scorer. Lacks a little confidence on offense.

column16: Is extremely creative and capable of seeing the play develop in slow motion. Makes excellent decisions when passing and shooting. Excels on power plays.
column17: Can get pushed off the puck easily, and lacks strength when lined up against towering NHL defenders. Has been known to go into scoring slumps.

column16: Has the physique to play a hitting game, but is also a polished checker. Will kill penalties and can be a solid leader in the room.
column17: Skating is his Achilles' heel. Doesn't possess top-line talent and has always been prone to serious injury.

column16: Has great size and reach. Is good on face-offs and does the little things in order to survive the pro game. Can play both center or right wing.
column17: Has skating issues. Was supposed to put up much bigger offensive numbers in the pros but has been a major flop in terms of production.

column16: Is at his best when he goes one-on-one against top forwards, since he can shut the best down with intimidation and poise. Has an accurate point shot, great size, sound hockey sense, decent mobility and an exemplary work ethic.
column17: Doesn't put up significant offensive numbers. Is a little bit too hesitant with the puck on his stick, since he's not a natural stick-handler. Can be guilty of being a little too aggressive at times.

column16: Has a great blend of size and mobility. Owns a lightning-quick glove hand. Is very confident in his puck-handling ability.
column17: Must continue to work on his concentration. Has not shown an ability to step up as a starting goalkeeper at the NHL level.

column16: Has prototypical NHL size. Loves to bang bodies. Moves the puck efficiently and is defensively responsible.
column17: Needs more work on his coordination and lateral mobility. Has limited offensive upside. Must stay away from serious injury.

column16: Can throw them with the best in the business. Knows how to stir the pot and rile up opponents. Has made the conversion from defense to right wing.
column17: Is limited to journeyman status because of a lack of fundamental skills. Looks lost on the ice the more he plays.

column16: Has tremendous size for a goaltender. Shows a good glove hand and the ability to play the puck effectively. Has settled nicely into a backup role.
column17: Needs more work on his quickness and ability to recover when he's on the ground. Is too inconsistent, which is why he failed as a starting goalkeeper.

column16: Loves to play a crash-and-bang game down the wing. Is defensively aware and displays leadership qualities. Works as hard as anyone on the ice.
column17: Needs to work on his skating. Lacks the talent needed to produce regularly in the NHL.

column16: Loves to play a physical game from behind the blue-line. Keeps things simple and knows his limitations. Is a willing pugilist and solid team player.
column17: Has limited offensive acumen. His skating ability is suspect. Tends to struggle when lined up against shifty NHL forwards.

column16: Possesses size and strength in spades, as well as better-than-average mobility when opposed against speedy forwards. Can play a shutdown role.
column17: Injuries have hindered his performance. Also, his offensive ability is limited, since he hasn't put up big numbers at any level. Can take bad penalties.

column16: Has tremendous size for a rearguard. Moves well for a big guy and is not afraid of laying on the body. Displays good offensive instincts. Is also willing to drop the gloves, if need be.
column17: Needs more discipline and must avoid taking bad penalties. Has trouble with players taking him to the outside and should continue to work on his coordination.

column16: Is a solid technical goaltender and gets himself in perfect position to make routine stops most of the time. Has good bloodlines, since his father Bob was a longtime NHL goalie.
column17: Has so far struggled to live up to lofty expectations. Needs to prove he can rebound from adversity. Isn't confident enough in his own ability.

column16: Has tremendous size for the goaltending position, so he fills up most of the net. Is capable of making spectacular saves from time to time, and is also a great team-first guy.
column17: Consistency has always eluded him at the National Hockey League level. Has questionable lateral mobility, which hurts his overall effectiveness.

column16: Is a hulking figure and an asset when he intimidates the opposition. Can win fights and is always willing to stick up for his teammates.
column17: Doesn't skate very well, which limits the amount of ice time he can handle at the NHL level. Will never be confused with a scorer in the offensive zone.

column16: Has prototypical NHL size and likes to use it to his advantage. Usually limits mistakes in his own end. Can be quite physical from the back end and also drop the gloves when necessary.
column17: Is extremely limited in the offensive zone, which makes him less appealing as a top-four blueliner at the NHL level. Also has skating issues.

column16: Has incredible imagination with the puck and excellent playmaking ability. Likes to shoot the puck often when playing the point on the power play. Is a leader by example.
column17: Isn't big or physical, so he can wear down against bigger opposing centers. His defensive game has regressed over time.

column16: Is usually among the most industrious skaters on the ice. Displays a sound two-way game and some offensive ability. Has good size and strength. Is strong in the corners and in front of the opposing goal.
column17: Will never be confused with a natural goal-scorer. Doesn't always take full advantage of his imposing frame. Misses a lot of quality scoring chances. Lacks intensity from time to time.

column16: Has great size and athleticism. Is tough, intelligent and displays a strong work ethic. Plays a sound two-way game.
column17: Needs to maximize his size and strength in the corners. Must continue to work on his coordination.

column16: Has good size and decent offensive ability from the back end. Is very experienced for the minor-pro level.
column17: Has never proven capable of taking the next step to the big league. Needs to use his 6-1 frame more to his advantage.

column16: Always plays an in-your-face style and is well suited for the North American game. Kills penalties effectively. Has plenty of versatility. Excels in shootouts.
column17: Doesn't own top-end offensive skills. Has a tendency to deliver questionable hits, which often rile up the opposition and hurt his team.

column16: Is a no-nonsense type behind the blueline and never takes any prisoners. Hits everything that moves and plays with tremendous passion.
column17: Lacks both defensive polish and offensive upside. Must prove he can come all the way back from serious knee problems.

column16: Plays the body well. Is defensively aware and displays energy on every shift. Can play the role of shift disturber. Kills penalties with aplomb.
column17: Lacks the offensive skills needed to play a top-six role in the NHL. Will occasionally run into penalty trouble. Can go into long scoring droughts.

column16: Has great skating ability and work ethic. Hits anything that moves. Plays a gritty, in-your-face style and owns solid scoring instincts.
column17: Injuries have taken a major toll on his career, so it's still a concern. Over time, his body has broken down due to the punishment that comes with playing a power forward's role.

column16: Plays a safe brand of hockey that keeps the mistakes to a minimum. Is very durable and will play through injuries.
column17: Lacks the overall skills to contribute on offense consistently. Does not use his good size nearly enough.

column16: Is an extremely intelligent player and skates very well along the blueline. Can be a terrific power play quarterback and steadying influence from the back end.
column17: Doesn't have ideal size for an NHL blue-liner and tends to get knocked off the puck from time to time. Can wear down with overuse.

column16: Has excellent size and agility. Is a confident goalkeeper with the potential to take over a game.
column17: Is still not all the way back from a serious groin injury that cost him the entire 2001-02 season. Needs to play with more consistency in the pro ranks.

column17: Is still a work in progress in terms of lateral movement and overall flexibility. Needs to display more consistency to land a permanent NHL gig.

column16: Has good speed and offensive instincts. Can be a productive player at the minor-pro level when given a lot of ice time.
column17: Is too small for the National Hockey League game and lacks significant bulk. Struggles without the puck and in the defensive zone.

column17: Is extremely limited in terms of natural offensive ability. May sometimes take a bad penalty to put his team behind the eight-ball.

column16: Can put up good numbers at lower levels, mainly due to solid offensive instincts.
column17: Is an undersized defenseman for the NHL game. Needs more work without the puck.

column17: Lacks the skill required to play a top-six role in the NHL. Also needs more work on his play without the puck.

column17: Lacks the refined skills of upper-echelon netminders, so he will have to work twice as hard just to stick in the big league in any capacity.

column16: Is always willing to protect his teammates, as well as stir the pot when necessary.
column17: Lacks the requisite skills to play a regular role at the National Hockey Level.

column17: Doesn't have a lot of upside on offense, but must also improve his defensive game in order to see more ice time.

column17: Lacks the offensive acumen needed to play a regular shift at a speedier pace in the NHL. Must curb his penchant for taking bad penalties.

column17: Will always need to outwork opponents, as he can't make it on talent alone. Can occasionally take a bad penalty that hurts his team.

column17: Is somewhat prone to injuries, especially to his lower body, which is a direct result of his gung-ho approach to every game. Needs to better learn how to pace himself.

column17: Needs to play with greater consistency from game to game when in the big league. Must avoid taking bad penalties that hurt his team.
